<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Denounces U.S. Congress Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) warned today
that a non-abiding U.S. Congress resolution on moving the
U.S. Embassy from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem will obstruct the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
AL Assistant Secretary General for Political Affairs Mohamed
Zakaria voiced his strong astonishment over the resolution.
</P>
<P>
"It will impede Arab, international and American efforts to
salvage the peace process from its present stalemate caused by
Israeli arbitrary measures," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. House of Representatives voted Tuesday 406-17 calling
on President Bill Clinton to reaffirm that Jerusalem must remain
Israel's "undivided capital."
</P>
<P>
The vote, which does not oblige the Clinton administration to
act, came as Egypt struggled to resolve a peacemaking crisis
between Israel and the Palestinian Authority caused by Israel's
construction in March of a new Jewish settlement in Arab East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israel captured East Jerusalem in 1967 and annexed it in a move
unrecognized by the international community, including the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Zakaria voiced the hope that Clinton would not implement the
said resolution especially as the crisis of the
Palestinian-Israeli negotiations has reached its peak.
</P>
<P>
"Such resolution would lead to a state of frustration among all
peace advocates," Assistant Secretary General for Palestinian
Affairs Saeed Kamal said.
</P>
<P>
These resolutions certainly place Arab and Islamic countries
before serious challenges, Kamal warned.
</P>
<P>
In October 1995, the U.S. Senate and the House passed the
Jerusalem Embassy Act which states as a matter of U.S. policy that
Jerusalem should remain "the undivided capital of Israel" and the
American embassy should be moved there by May 1999.
</P>
<P>
But recognizing the volatility of the issue, it allowed Clinton
to suspend the embassy's move from Tel Aviv for a six-month period.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians, who want East Jerusalem as their future
capital, have said that recognizing the annexation of Jerusalem to
Israel and opening an embassy there without recognizing East
Jerusalem as the capital of Palestine is a declaration of war on
the Palestinian people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
