<HEADLINE> Lesotho Govt Warns Against Public Servants' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The Lesotho government today
warned public servants and all workers that should they fail to report
for duty on Monday it would not support them if their employers took
action against them, reported the South African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho Prime Minister Ntsu Mokhehle's Special Adviser, Thom
Thabane, was quoted as saying in Maseru, capital of the land-locked
kingdom, that any planned protest action to stay away from work was
illegal.
</P>
<P>
Thabane also stressed that the government was also an employer
and if any of its employees failed to turn up for work on Monday
it would also not support them.
</P>
<P>
A coalition of opposition parties led by the ruling Basutoland
Congress Party (BCP) has called a series of protest action
against Mokhehle's latest political moves, which have reportedly
plunged Lesotho into a constitutional crisis.
</P>
<P>
Mokhehle last weekend broke away from the BCP and formed a new
political party, the Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD), to
which he immediately transferred governance, a move which stunned
the small kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The coalition rejected Mokhehle's political move and vowed to make
Lesotho ungovernable and parliament unworkable.
</P>
<P>
Monday's planned stayaway call is one of a number of protest
actions called by the opposition. enditem

=06151624

=06151638
