<HEADLINE> Jordan Condemns U.S. Congress Decision on Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 15 (Xinhua) - Jordan here today condemned the
U.S. Congress' decision to recognize Jerusalem as Israel's capital
as "unappropriate."
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. Congress' move precipitates the peace process and the
Oslo accord which has pulled the entire Israeli issue on the
agenda of final status negotiations," Jordanian Prime Minister
Abdul Salam Majali told the press here today.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, the Jordian Lower House, represented by Speaker
Saad Hayel Srour, said that the move by the U.S. congressmen was
aimed at aborting the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, King Hussein of Jordan warned in Geneva on his
European visit that the U.S. House of Representatives' resolution
calling on President Bill Clinton to reaffirm that Jerusalem must
remain Israel's undivided capital "sort of undermined" the
U.S. role in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. efforts in May to reactivate the peace negotiations
between the Palestinians and Israel came to no avail as its special
envoy Dennis Ross failed to persuade Israel to make concessions.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has a close military relationship with the U.S. It will
receive the first batch of 16 F-16 jet fighters, part of a
300-million-dollar military assistance pledged by the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and the U.S. have just concluded their second allied
war games this year, named "Infinite Moonlight 1997," on June 11.
</P>
</TEXT>
