<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Boycott Mideast Economic Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez
Boueiz announced here today that his country will not participate
in the Middle East economic summit scheduled for November 19 in
Doha, Qatar, which will expectedly be attended by Israel.
</P>
<P>
He also called on other Arab countries to boycott the Doha
summit since Lebanon considers such a conference a step forward to
the normalization of ties between the Arabs and Israel and an
equivalent to Arab-Israeli multi-lateral peace talks.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held in his Beirut residence, the
foreign minister recalled the resolutions which were taken
earlier this year in the Arab League summit in Cairo, the summit
of the Islamic Conference Organization in Islamabad and the
meeting of the ICO's Jerusalem committee in Rabat.
</P>
<P>
Those resolutions, Boueiz underlined, "demand all the Arab
states to freeze relations with Israel and to review the ties they
had set up, in light of the stalemate in the peace process and in
light of the negative positions taken by Israel."
</P>
<P>
"We consider it a violation of these resolutions to carry on
any conference or work which could be linked with the
normalization, the multi-lateral negotiations and an enhancement
of relations between the Arab countries and Israel," he underlined.
</P>
<P>
"We will absolutely not participate in the economic conference
in Qatar, and we called on the Arab brothers to show a firm and
clear position through boycotting this conference," Boueiz added.
</P>
<P>
Instead of the Middle East economic conference, the foreign
minister called for an "Arab economic conference" in order to
draw the Arab economic strategies by which the Arabs will
negotiate with world states on economic issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
