<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-15 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rafsanjani Denies Iran Hosts PKK Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Hashemi
Rafsanjani said here today that there were no rebels of the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) on the Iranian territory.
</P>
<P>
Following a 40-minute meeting with his Turkish counterpart
Suleyman Demirel, Rafsanjani told reporters that Iran and Turkey
would set up cooperative teams to curb the PKK activities along
the Iranian-Turkish borders.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has repeatedly accused Iran of supporting the PKK
rebels, which has been fighting a separatist war for autonomy in
eastern and southeastern Turkey since August 1984.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani said that Iran and Turkey should strengthen
security cooperation along their border areas.
</P>
<P>
Describing Turkey as a friendly country, the Iranian president
said that the infiltration of the PKK rebels into Iran also
affects the benefits of the Iranian people.
</P>
<P>
Iran has criticized Turkey for launching a large-scale
military operation in northern Iraq aimed at wiping out the PKK
rebels there.
</P>
<P>
About 50,000-strong Turkish government troops, backed by
artillery and fighters, poured into northern Iraq on May 14 to
attack the PKK rebels, who allegedly constitute the most dangerous
threat to the Turkish security.
</P>
<P>
In response to a Xinhua question earlier today, Turkish
Foreign Ministry Spokesman Omer Akbel denied media reports that
Turkey had begun to withdraw its troops from northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 PKK militants have reportedly been killed in
the latest Turkish military incursion in northern Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
