<HEADLINE> No Pact Deal Expected on Sunday: Dutch Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The Dutch presidency of the
European Union said that it was not seeking to strike a deal on
the EMU(Economic and Monetary Union) stability pact at an EU
finance ministers' dinner on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
"The presidency does not intend to strike deals tonight over
dinner," a Dutch spokesman told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman emphasised that the dinner was only an informal
occasion at which the issue was to be discussed.
</P>
<P>
The finance ministers' informal discussion comes before a
summit of EU leaders on Monday and Tuesday, which was supposed to
agree on a new EU treaty, preparing the 15-nation bloc to face the
challenges in the next century.
</P>
<P>
But the meeting seems set to be dominated by a rift which has
emerged between France and Germany since the new French government
said last week that it needed more time to study the stability
pact, which sets strict rules to keep deficits under control after
the launch of the EMU on January 1, 1999.  
</P>
</TEXT>
