<HEADLINE> Egypt, Turkey to Strengthen Trade Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa told reporters here today that Egypt and Turkey wished to
double their trade volume soon.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark following a 30-minute meeting between
Turkish President Suleyman Demirel and Egyptian Prime Minister
Kamal el-Ganzouri, who is here to attend the first summit of eight
Muslim countried -- developing eight, or D-8 -- held earlier today.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that the two leaders discussed commercial and
economic ties between their two countries, whose trade volume
stands at half a billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Demirel and Ganzouri exchanged views over the
stalled Middle East peace process and the latest developments in
northern Iraq, said Moussa.
</P>
<P>
In a Saturday meeting with Turkish Prime Minister Necmettin
Erbakan, Ganzouri urged Turkey to end its massive military
operation in northern Iraq which was aimed at wiping out the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Mubarak failed to turn out at the first D-8
summit in Istanbul, Turkey's largest city, in protest over
Turkey's military incursion into northern Iraq which started on
May 14, an Egyptian diplomat told Xinhua Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The D-8 group, consisting of Turkey, Iran, Nigeria, Egypt,
Pakistan, Bangledesh, Malaysia and Indonesia, was formed on
October 11, 1996 on the auspices of Erbakan. It is aimed at
expanding economic cooperation among the Muslim countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
