<HEADLINE> Britain Vows to Ease N.Irish Parades Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Britain is trying to step up
efforts to solve the imminent parades crisis in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Mo Mowlam, the Northern Ireland Secretary, announced today that
she would hold talks with pro-British Protestant marching groups
and Irish Catholic objectors.
</P>
<P>
"The government is determined to do all we can to avoid a
repeat of last year's appalling events, which the people of
Northern Ireland have made absolutely clear they don't want to
see," she said.
</P>
<P>
Last year Northern Ireland suffered its worst street violence
for decades when police imposed a ban on a Protestant march in
Portadown but reversed it after four days of riots and roadblocks
by pro-British "Loyalists".
</P>
<P>
Mowlam's announcement came amid signs of continuing deadlock
about a planned July 6 march from Portadown, ahead of the Orange
Order's mammoth "Twelfth of July" parades which celebrate ancient
victories over the native Irish.
</P>
<P>
The secretary said she would hold meetings with key groups
which she met within days of her appointment after Labor won the
landslide election on May 1.
</P>
<P>
"As of this week, I, along with senior officials, will
undertake an intensive round of discussions with all the relevant
parties. This will continue over the course of the next few
weeks," she said.
</P>
<P>
The tension over parades is adding to community fears sparked
by a renewal of hostilities by the Irish Republican Army and their
Loyalist rivals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
