<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-15 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Congress Move Seen Blow to Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez
Boueiz said here today that the Middle East peace process
suffered "another blow" from a U.S. congress resolution on
Jerusalem adopted Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that the timing of this resolution came to blow the
peace process again rather than to safeguard it," the foreign
minister told a press conference in his Beirut residence.
</P>
<P>
In the non-binding resolution, the U.S. House of
Representatives called on the Clinton administration to recognize
Jerusalem as the "undivided capital" of Israel and to allocate
100 million dollars to move the U.S. embassy from Tel Aviv to
Jerusalem, the city shrined by both Arabs and Jews.
</P>
<P>
"I think the principle of this resolution totally contradicts
the principles of the peace process...which demands that the
status of the holy city should be negotiated," Boueiz pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
These principles requires that "the things not be preempted by
this kind of position," he said. "Additionally, I believe that
the resolution harms the role of the United States as an
arbitrator and mediator in the peace process" which is supposedly
to be "impartial".
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister described a resolution endorsed by the
U.N. general assembly Friday blaming Israel for the shelling of a
U.N. peacekeeping force camp in south Lebanon last year as an
"important victory" for Lebanon and other countries voting in
favor of it.
</P>
<P>
He vowed his government will continue demanding compensation
for all the damages caused by Israel in the 17-day-long "Grapes of
Wrath" operation in south Lebanon in April, 1996, and will study
the means to make the demands met.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. general assembly's resolution called on Israel to pay
1.7 million dollars to the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL)
as part of the multi-national force's 1997-1998 budget, to atone
for the Jewish state's culpability in the shelling of the UNIFIL's
camp at Qana on April 18, 1996.
</P>
<P>
One hundred and twenty seven states voted in favor of the
resolution while Israel and the U.S. voted against and Russia
abstained. The paragraph in the draft dealing with the damages
assessment against Israel was put to a separate vote and received
66 votes in favor and 59 abstentions with U.S. and Israel
opposing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
