<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Tough Talks Ahead for EU Amsterdam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The colorful Dutch capital of
Amsterdam is the venue for the European Union government leaders
to try to finalize the review of the Maastricht Treaty on June 16
and 17.
</P>
<P>
An agreement in Amsterdam will pave the way for the start of the
process for expanding the 15-nation bloc eastwards, which is set
to be one of the key challenges as it enters the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
However, the 158-page draft Treaty, prepared by the EU Dutch
presidency and due to be submitted to EU Heads of State and
Government, seems to have dashed the high hopes expressed earlier
on in the Treaty renegotiating process.
</P>
<P>
The text is the culmination of 15 months of negotiations,
formally dubbed the Inter-governmental Conference, aimed at
streamlining EU decision-making ahead of enlargement.
</P>
<P>
On the most controversial subjects, such as institutional
reforms, the draft Treaty fails to inspire universal support.
</P>
<P>
In the intense bargaining which can be expected at Amsterdam,
some of the proposed reforms may be watered down to allow all the
EU leaders to emerge as political victors.
</P>
<P>
Before being able to adopt them, they will have to strike a
deal on a new economic and social dimension to the pact on
stability and growth.
</P>
<P>
The draft text has a long, new chapter on employment, largely
to allay fears by the new French government that the strict budget
rules set out in the pact will undermine the bloc's efforts to
fight unemployment, which currently affects one in nine EU
citizen.
</P>
<P>
Although almost all EU leaders are fairly optimistic that the
new Treaty would be signed on Tuesday, they are nontheless facing
difficult negotiations on several issues, including these:
</P>
<P>
Institutions. Britain, France and Germany want to enhance their
influence within the Union, but the Dutch draft treaty more or
less puts off any reform to the EU and its institutions until the
next wave of enlargement. Bowing to the pressure of small states.
</P>
<P>
Employment. The EU leaders are expected to finalize the
drafting of a Title on Employment, one of the big innovations of
the new treaty. It will attach the same importance and procedures
to job-creation efforts as the Maastricht treaty gave to the
single-currency deficit and inflation criteria. But the text has
been amended and made more precise to allay german fears of having
to dip into the Community budget to fund job boosting measures.
</P>
<P>
Foreign policy. Six countries - France, Germany, Belgium,
Luxembourg, Italy and Spain - have called for the incorporation
into the Treaty of the objective of an eventual merger of the
European defense club the Western Union into the EU and the
introduction of a Protocol defining the stages of and strategy for
this merger. Britain, supported by the "neutral" member states, is
opposed to the idea. The Dutch text merely alluded to the draft
Protocol.
</P>
<P>
Interior policies. The new text makes it virtually impossible
in the future for qualified majority decisions to be taken to
determine a common immigration policy and the conditions for
crossing the EU's external borders. The measures, which allow
Britain and Ireland to continue border checks, provides little
hope for any change in the reform of the EU's Third Pillar, which
focuses on cooperation on justice and home affairs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
