<HEADLINE> Demobilised Boy Soldiers Demonstrate in Sierra </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Over 100 demobilised boy
soldiers demonstrated at the headquarters of the Children
Assosciated with the War (CAW) Program in Freetown Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators, aged between 11 and 19, carried banners
with the inscription "We Need More Support Not Closure of the
Program" and "CAW Officials Are Not Giving Us Our Due".
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators threatened to burn down the three-storeyed
building but were restrained by security guards.
</P>
<P>
According to 16-year-old Morie Raogers, head of the
demonstrators#,food and other basic amenities have not been
supplied to them for six weeks now.
</P>
<P>
"We decided to demonstrate when we heard that the program was
going to close", he added.
</P>
<P>
Another demonstrator, Salieu Murray, who became a boy soldier
for the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF) at the age of
seven in 1992, said the CAW program "completely rehabitalitated"
him.
</P>
<P>
"Now they want to leave us in the cold and just close down
like that, we need more information", he added.
</P>
<P>
A CAW senior official dismissed the claim of closure as
"baseless".
</P>
<P>
"We've been having problems of funding for the past month and
it has been worsened by the May 25 coup. Everything will be
sorted out soon and the boys will be happy once more", she added.
</P>
<P>
CAW was established four years ago by UNICEF to provide some
social needs including education for former child combatants who
had fought alongside government troops or rebels between 1991 and
1996.
</P>
<P>
According to UN statistics, in 1993 an estimated 2,000
children associated with the military in Sierra Leone were later
demobilised after the country signed the Rights of the Child
Convention in 1995.
</P>
<P>
"1,000 children fought with the RUF and it was extremely
difficult to demobilise them as the rebel organisation was
extremely hostile to our program", a UNICEF official told Xinhua.
</P>
</TEXT>
