<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Waigel: No Tax Increases in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Under huge pressure from within the
German governing coalition, German Finance Minister Theo Waigel
today clearly indicated that there will be no tax increases to
finance the German government budget in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"Under current circumstances tax increases are difficult to
realize and hardly desirable," said Waigel in the southern German
resort of Bad Woerishofen.
</P>
<P>
Waigel, who has been declining to totally rule out the
possibility of tax increases so far, was also quoted by German
media as saying on Saturday that tax hikes would not be
politically realizable and would also be unfavorable for the
German economy.
</P>
<P>
With these remarks, Waigel has apparently gave in to the strong
opposition from the Free Democratic Party (FDP), the junior
partner in the Bonn ruling coalition, which has categorically
rejected tax increases as measures to finance budget.
</P>
<P>
Germany is currently struggling with serious financial plight
against the backdrop of nearly record unemployment and an expected
18 billion German mark (about 10.6 billion U.S. dollar) shortfall
in the tax revenues for 1997.
</P>
<P>
To plug the huge budget hole and to help the country to meet
the strict qualification requirements for the planned single
European currency, Waigel had originally proposed to revalue
upwards the central bank's gold and foreign currency reserves, but
had to retreat from the plan eventually under strong protests from
the central bank and other European countries.
</P>
<P>
As an alternative to tax increases, Waigel said Sunday that the
government would have to consider further cuts in public spendings
in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
