<HEADLINE> Sudanese President Welcomes Return of Opponents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese President Omar
Al-Bashir said here today that his government welcomed the return
of all opponents from abroad provided they commit themselves to
patriotism.
</P>
<P>
Al-Bashir made the remarks during his meeting with Sharif Zein
al-Abdeen Hindi, secretary general of the banned National
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
Hindi returned to Sudan last week from Damascus, Syria, after
eight years in exile, in a bid to try to bridge the gap between
the Islamic government and the opposition.
</P>
<P>
Hindi, one of the first government opponents to return to
Sudan, told reporters after the meeting that he discussed with
Al-Bashir "the Shura" (advisory) issue and how to reach a way for
peaceful power exchange in the country as well as the proper way
of introducing democracy to Sudan.
</P>
<P>
He added that his initiative is to allow all political forces
to express their views openly on all the national issues.
</P>
<P>
He is going to hold popular rallies over the coming days
in order to "enlarge the circle of dialogue and launch the
initiative of national dialogue among all the walks of life in
Sudan," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
