<HEADLINE> Religious Group in S. Leone Denounces Coupists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The Inter Religious Council
(IRC) in Sierra Leone, an umbrella group of Moslems,
Christians and traditional leaders, today denounced the military
junta of the May 25 coup that toppled the civilian government.
</P>
<P>
An IRC spokesman said that many attempts had proved abortive
since May 27 to discuss the current state of insecurity in the
country, with Major Johnny Koroma, leader of the junta Armed
Forces Revolutionary Council (AFRC).
</P>
<P>
"As we call on the AFRC to hand over power to the ousted
civilian government of Tejan Kabbah, we are also ready to assist
in facilitating any form of negotiated settlement to end the
present impasse," the IRC said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
It also urged the international community "to continue its
search for a peaceful resolution of the conflict," according to a
report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
A week ago, a letter from the IRC was sent to all churches and
mosques in the capital Freetown, criticizing the coup and calling
for the restoration of the ousted civilian government.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the letter received a mixed response
as some Christians and Moslems urged the IRC "to pressurize the
junta into bowing out of office without precondition."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ruling AFRC warned what it called "some ill
disposed persons to stop intimidating and harassing relatives and
friends of former politicians and religious leaders."
</P>
<P>
In a released broadcast on the state radio, the junta stressed
that "the revolution (referring to the May 25 coup) is not out to
witchhunt anybody. All those engaged in such actions should stop
it immediately."
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, a local independent FM station reported that
the Roman Catholic Archbishop, Joseph Ganda, had fled to country,
but this was denied on Friday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
