<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stable as a Financial Center, Expert (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong should be able to
maintain it's role as the financial center of Asia, according to
an expert familiar with Asia business.
</P>
<P>
Eliot R. Clauss, President of the U.S.-China Chamber of
Commerce (USCCC), said during a recent interview with Xinhua that
Hong Kong should be able to maintain such a role in the
foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
Prior to China's resumption of the exercise of sovereignty over
Hong Kong, the region's economy was listed as among the most
competitive in the world by the Geneva-based World Economic Forum,
as well as the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Mr. Clauss, who travels frequently to the Chinese mainland and
Hong Kong, opined the openness and well established financial
system of Hong Kong business environment will continue to attract
numerous foreign investments after July 1.
</P>
<P>
The USCCC was found in New York in 1993 by a group of Chinese
and American entrepreneurs who are enthusiastic to promote
U.S.-China business relationship. The USCCC's Chairman is former
U.S. President George Bush's elder brother, Prescott S. Bush, Jr.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Clauss commented that the prime geographic location,
well-established financial systems, open securities policy and a
comprehensive legal system -- all these elements contributed to
Hong Kong's remarkable achievement today.
</P>
<P>
He also said that there is a saying that Shanghai will be a
substitute for Hong Kong as the Asia financial center -- many
westerners acknowledge this supposition. Mr. Clauss said Shanghai
is indeed developing rapidly, particularly it is amazing to see
the development in the Pudong New Area.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said historically Shanghai was a very important
business center. Following decades of development, it has
developed to have many of the conditions that are required to
transform itself as the Asia financial center. If Shanghai can
provide a stable and friendly legal system for foreign investors
and a highly efficient investment environment, there is a
possibility that Shanghai will surpass Hong Kong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stable as a Financial Center, Expert (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, Mr. Clauss also said that there is still room for
improvement and development of Shanghai. For instance, he noted,
the Shanghai Stock Exchange is only beginning to establish its
system and policy. Comparing it with the New York and Hong Kong
stock exchanges, the Shanghai Stock Exchange is like a teenager
who has just started to reach out. An example to illustrate this
procedure would be similar to training a professional athlete, he
said, it requires tremendous amount of training and proper
training strategies, more importantly, it takes time. The result
simply cannot be achieved in a short period of time.
</P>
<P>
While it is clearly difficult to predict the long term outcome,
Mr. Clauss said he believes that for the next five to ten years at
least, Hong Kong will retain its status as the financial center of
Asia. Among the reasons for this is simply that western business
is accustomed to and familiar with doing business there.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, he said, if Shanghai continues to develop in ways
attractive to western business, more companies may be attracted to
Shanghai. Given the extensive development of Shanghai and the
surrounding region, and the many industrial companies in the
region, Shanghai is likely to continue to attract western
investment and trade. This will be especially true if the
financial and service sector, including the Shanghai Stock
Exchange, become more open to foreign investment. The more the
financial and service sectors operate consistent with
international standards, the more attractive Shanghai will be to
western business, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Clauss commented that generally investors are attracted to
developing markets, especially if the infrastructure and legal
system are well developed. The price of real estate -- for
offices, factories and housing -- the price of labor and the
quality of the labor force, the ease of transportation and
communications, the free flow of information, the openness of the
banking system, the tax rates and the level of government
oversight and regulation, are all factors that western investors
will consider when choosing between Shanghai and Hong Kong as a
place to do business.
</P>
<P>
As most people have an optimistic outlook for Hong Kong, it is
likely to remain an important financial and commercial center,
according to Mr. Clauss. He said he believes that the questions of
whether Hong Kong can sustain its role as an international
financial center after the handover, and whether Shanghai or some
other city ultimately replace Hong Kong as the financial center of
Asia, are questions that can be -- and will be -- answered only by
the marketplace.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
