<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Election Campaign to Kick off in Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The 11 Liberian presidential candidates
will kick off their election campaign on Monday, as an internationally
monitered peace process is coming to its final stage.
</P>
<P>
The election on July 19 will lead to the final end of a civil war
that has killed more than 200,000 people and left more others homelss
since 1989.
</P>
<P>
The last election that was held in this west African country was in
1985, when Samuel Doe was elected as the president. The civil war
broke out four years later, when Charles Taylor launched his attack on
the government army on the eve of the 1989 Christmas.
</P>
<P>
The coming election will be a culmination of the revised Abuja peace
accord signed by the warring factions in August 1996, which is the
13th peace pact reached by the factions in the seven-year war.
</P>
<P>
Charles Taylor, now as the leader of the National Patriotic Party,
will be one of the key players in the race for presidency.
</P>
<P>
"I am the only strong person to lead this country following seven
years of war," he told reporters at a recent rally.
</P>
<P>
Taylor is campaigning on a ticket of national unity and
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Two other major warlords, Alhaji Kromah and George Boley are also
in the race, as the leader of the All Liberia Coalition Party and the
National Democratic Party, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Kromah's platform stresses the importance of international and
regional security in exploiting natural resources and promoting
economic reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
Contesting against the former warlords is the Ellen
Johnson-Sirleaf, the only woman candidate. She was a former
minister and until recently a senior official at the United
Nations Development Program.
</P>
<P>
Johnson-Sirleaf represents the Unity Party and enjoys the backing
of the True Whig Party, which ruled Liberia for more than a century.
</P>
<P>
Cletus Wotorson, a former minister, runs for the Liberia
Unification Party and the Liberia Action Party.
</P>
<P>
Former chief justice Chea Cheapoo and former Vice-President Harry
Moniba represent the Progressive People's Party and Liberia National
Union, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Observers said they would dwell on respect for the rule of law and
human rights, as well as the need to eliminate corruption in
government.
</P>
<P>
Other candidates include Gabriel Baccus Matthews of the United
People's Party, Togba Nah-Tipoteh of the Liberian People's Party and
Boima Fahnbulleh of the Reformation Alliance Party.
</P>
<P>
They have described themselves as "progressives into whose hands
the governance of Liberia must fall at this time".
</P>
<P>
As candidates are druming up their campaigns, preparations for the
election are said to be poor. Voters' education has not begun even in
the capital Monrovia, and polling centers have yet to be named.
</P>
<P>
Most importantly, the electoral commission has not got enough money
to do its work, according to its chairman, Henry Andrews.
</P>
<P>
In late May, the Liberian election, originally set for May
30, was shifted to July 19, because the candidates dared not
to go out of Monrovia on their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Victor Malu, the commander of the west African
peace-keeping force in Liberia has assurred them time and again that
security is now guaranteed for the election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
