<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll Shows Americans Softening on Immigration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Most Americans have regular
contact with new immigrants and are more accepting of them than a
few years ago, a poll released Sunday indicates.
</P>
<P>
Most of those surveyed said immigration has had little effect
on them or their communities, according to the national survey by
Knight-Ridder Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The poll of 1,314 whites, blacks and Hispanics, all citizens or
residents of the United States since at least 1980, was conducted
for Knight-Ridder by Princeton Survey Research Associates.
</P>
<P>
Forty-five percent of those polled said recent immigrants have
had a positive impact on the nation, 42 percent said immigrants
harm the nation as a whole, and 10 percent said the effects are
mixed.
</P>
<P>
The poll shows a drop in anti-immigration sentiment from the
pattern of 1993-1995 when 60 percent of Americans told pollsters
that the influx of foreigners was bad for the country and should
be reduced.
</P>
<P>
More than nine of 10 of those in the Knight-Ridder survey said
they regularly have contact with new immigrants, mostly as they
work or shop in places where immigrants work.
</P>
<P>
People who saw problems they traced to new immigrants rarely
cited them in their own neighborhoods. One in three of those
polled thought immigration creates big problems for the country,
but only one in 10 saw such problems in his own neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
The interviews were conducted from May 2 through May 26. The
margin of sampling error was plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's Schumacher Wins Canadian Grand Prix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Germany's racer Michael Schumacher
was declared winner of Grand Prix of Canada in Montreal today,
after the race was brought to an abrupt end by a collision.
</P>
<P>
France's Jean Alesi was ranked second, and Italy's Giancarlo
Fisichella third in the race, which was broadcast live by the
Canadian Broadcasting Corporation (CBC) Television.
</P>
<P>
Olivier Panis of France rammed into a tire wall on the 52nd lap
and was taken from the Gilles Villeneuve Circuit by ambulance.
</P>
<P>
The tire wall was scattered along the backside of the 2.75-mile
track, forcing race officials to call the race after 56 of a
scheduled 69 laps.
</P>
<P>
Canada's Jacques Villeneuve, who came into the race as the
points leader, fell out of the running after only 2 laps, when his
ties lost their grip and he went through a corner and into the
guard wall.
</P>
<P>
Schumacher, the two-time world champion and 1994 Canadian Grand
Prix champion, will reclaim points lead from Jacques Villeneuve,
37 points to 30.
</P>
<P>
A total of 11 cars were classified at the end of the race from
the starting field of 22 cars.
</P>
<P>
Today's race was the seventh of 17 in Grand Prix events in the
Formula One World Driving Championship.
</P>
<P>
The next event is to start in Magny-Cours, France on June 29th.
</P>
