<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Father of Father's Day Initiator Honored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The National Center for
Fathering is recognizing the woman credited with initiating
Father's Day more than 80 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The Kansas-based organization is honoring the late Sonora Smart
Dodd today by inducting her father, a Civil War veteran, into its
Fathering Hall of Fame, The United Press International reported.
</P>
<P>
Dodd was attending one of the first Mother's Day celebrations
in 1912 when she hit on the idea of Father's Day.
</P>
<P>
Her mother had died in childbirth, leaving her father, William
Jackson Smart, to raise his daughter by himself. Dodd thought a
national Father's Day would be a good way to honor his dedication
and sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
President Woodrow Wilson proclaimed Mother's Day as an annual
observance in 1915. But despite Dodd's efforts, fathers didn't
get their due until 1972, when Father's Day was officially
sanctioned by President Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
The seven-year-old National Center for Fathering established
its Hall of Fame last year. Although the group's honor roll
currently exists only on the Internet, organizers hope to build a
physical home eventually.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Peter Spokes says fathers can be nominated to the
Hall of Fame by their children or relatives, or they may be voted
in by the group's Board of Directors. In addition, the
organization is co-sponsoring Father of the Year contests around
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Leaders Start Tough Talks on New Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, June 16 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) leaders
started talks today at their two-day summit in Amsterdam to try to
reach an agreement on a new EU treaty that is supposed to prepare
the 15-nation bloc for the next century.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state and government almost immediately agreed
that an employment chapter should be incorporated into the new
treaty, making job creation a priority on EU's agenda, diplomats
said.
</P>
<P>
"(It) strikes a fair balance between efficient cooperation and
the realization that principal responsibility for employment rests
with member states," British Prime Minister Tony Blair was quoted
by an aide as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meeting at their twice-yearly meeting, the leaders are expected
to work on a draft treaty prepared by the Netherlands, the current
EU president, and then announce their agreement on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
But the draft treaty, a result of 15 months' tough
negotiations, still has a string of opt-outs and protocols.
</P>
<P>
Despite the eagerness of Britain, France and Germany to enhance
their influence within the union, the draft treaty, bowing to the
pressure of small states, virtually puts off any reform of the EU
and its institutions until the next wave of enlargement.
</P>
<P>
As for foreign policy issue, the draft merely alludes to a
draft protocol on a future merger between the EU and the Western
Union, the European defense club.
</P>
<P>
France, Germany, Belgium, Luxembourg, Italy and Spain have
called for the merger program to be included in the Treaty and
wanted a protocol mapping out the strategy and steps of the
merger. But Britain, supported by the "neutral" member states, is
opposed to the idea.
</P>
<P>
The draft also makes it virtually impossible in the future that
the EU members decide on a common immigration policy or a border
issue by qualified majority.
</P>
<P>
The draft, which allows Britain and Ireland to continue border
checks, is seen as a lack of progress in furthering the
cooperation among member states on judicial and home affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
