<HEADLINE> Maskhadov Launches Operation Against Crime in Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov
today decided to resume the Shield of Law operation against crime
in Chechnya, according to a report from it capital Grozny.
</P>
<P>
More than 3,000 men from all the law enforcement structures of
Chechnya were taking part in the operation, the Itar-Tass news
agency quoted Chechen Interior Minister Kazbek Makhashev as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The measures were taken, the minister said, to put an end to
the kidnapping of people, drug addiction, unlawful seizure of
housing facilities, and to enforce law and order in the petroleum
industry of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Besides, another operation named Hostages, was also launched
Sunday night. It is being carried out by a 300-man special team,
Makhashev said.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the Shield of Law operation, six hostages were
released from captivity today in Chechnya. The operation was
conducted by a group of the anti-terrorist center.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Maskhadov promised to "deal surprise and
lightning-fast strikes" in his crackdown on crime in Chechnya,
when the Russian Federation and the breakaway republic discussed
economic cooperation, including the transfer of Azerbaijiani
Caspian Sea of oil through Chechnya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
