<HEADLINE> EU to Decide Soon on Re-Importing East African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Union is expected to
announce by July 1 whether its 15 member countries will import
fish from Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania, the East African newspaper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The EU has imposed a temporary ban on fish imports from the three
eastern African countries on suspicion that their fish goods
contained the killer salmonella bacteria.
</P>
<P>
Europe is the largest market for eastern African fish and the
demand has grown following the scare caused by so-called mad cow
disease, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The three countries, which share Lake Victoria, the second
largest fresh water lake in the world and rich in popular
Nile perch, have the potential to meet a large part of Europe's
demand for fish.
</P>
<P>
A EU experts team inspected all fish factories, the hygiene
of fishing vessels, as well as the loading, transportation and
refrigeration of fish for export in the region last month.
</P>
<P>
The team also evaluated the capacity of local authorities on
fish to ensure that international standards are met and
maintained, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Countries which fail the test will be given a chance to
improve on the quality of their products and undergo another
inspection, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Laboratory tests made in Spain and Italy last year on samples
of frozen octopus imported from eastern Africa indicated that the
fish were contaminated with salmonella bacteria.
</P>
<P>
The two countries called for a total ban on fish from Kenya
and Uganda in 1996 but were persuaded by other EU members to wait
until a common standard could be worked out for all EU countries.
</P>
<P>
Kenya has 35 registered fish processing firms and earned 47
million Shillings (840,000 U.S. Dollars) from fishing industry
last year.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania exported 5,385 tons of frozen fish fillet of Nile
perch during the same period, fetching 12.6 million Dollars. The
exports of marine products account for 4.3 percent of the
country's total exports.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has nine fish processing plants which produce up to
220,000 tons of fresh water fish worth some 110 million Dollars a
year and employs about 60,000 people directly and more than
500,000 indirectly. enditem

=06161451

=06161455
NNNN
22:56 22:57 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
