<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Expects Five Percent GDP Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's economy is to grow by
five percent this year despite the lower-than-expected
agricultural output and an upward trend in lending rates.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's central bank, the Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe said in
its latest quarterly economic and statistical review today that
agriculture, manufacturing and mining will contribute to the five
percent growth.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture, despite the downward revision in output growth due to
excessive rains that affected crop yields in some areas, is expected
to grow by four percent in real terms.
</P>
<P>
''With output from most crops expected to exceed the 1996 levels,
agriculture is estimated to contribute 22 percent to overall GDP,''
the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing, largely benefiting from agriculture, is expected to
grow by seven percent and contribute 20 percent to GDP, while mining
production which fell 0.2 percent last year due to a fall in metal
prices is expected to grow by eight percent and contribute 6.5
percent to GDP.
</P>
<P>
However, the bank had also predicated its estimates on the
positive impact of reduced bank lending rates from 28-32 percent
range to 25-26 percent, which were expected to provide relief to
companies constrained by the high cost of borrowing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
