<HEADLINE> Dhaka Plans to Build Dam Over Ganges River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government is
planning to build a barrage over the Ganges to ensure integrated
development of water resources in the river's basin within
Bangladesh, according to Water Resources Minister Abdur Razzak.
</P>
<P>
The dam would help provide safety to 40 million people in
south-west Bangladesh and the Sundarbans, the largest natural
mangrove forest in the world, Razzak told a workshop here today.
</P>
<P>
Under a 30-year Ganges water sharing treaty signed in New Delhi
last December, Bangladesh is assured of getting half of the Ganges
river flow. The treaty paved the way for constructing a barrage
over the common river between Bangladesh and India.
</P>
<P>
Razzak said foreign development partners had already shown
interest in conducting feasibility and detailed engineering
studies for the Ganges barrage.
</P>
<P>
He said both Bangladesh and India had been monitoring the
implementation of the treaty since its signing and that
transparency for it would be created.
</P>
<P>
Razzak said the Joint River Commission has also been
reactivated to deal with unresolved issues of sharing the water of
53 other common rivers between Bangladesh and India.
</P>
<P>
The commission would help find out a solution to the problem of
water sharing of the Teesta and other rivers, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
