<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5 Killed in Rebels' Ambush in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Five people were killed and five
others wounded early this morning when a band of Philippine
leftist rebels ambushed a group of government soldiers along a
highway in the central Philippines, a senior military officer
said.
</P>
<P>
Col. Marcial Collao, commander of the Philippine Army 203rd
Brigade, said about 30 members of the rebel New People's Army
(NPA) ambushed the soldiers of the Army's 76th Infantry Battalion
riding a jeep on a highway in Camarines Norte province.
</P>
<P>
Among the killed were two soldiers and two civilians riding in
a private vehicle caught in the heavy gunfire, he said. An NPA
member was also killed.
</P>
<P>
Traffic went to a standstill along the national highway due to
the incident, stalling hundreds of vehicles for more than three
hours in both directions.
</P>
<P>
Collao said he had ordered a pursuit operation against the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
The NPA, the military wing of the leftist National Democratic
Front (NDF), has fought the government forces since its creation
in the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
The NDF's insurgency reached its peak in the early 1980s, with
the NPA's membership expanding to over 10,000 and its operation
covering the entire country.
</P>
<P>
But the NPA's strength was greatly weakened in the early 1990s
after the government launched an all-out war against it.
</P>
<P>
Due to differences over peace talks with the government, the
NPA has been fragmented in recent years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
