<HEADLINE> Teenagers in Shanghai Paint the Future of Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Two hundred youngsters from
around the city gathered today at the Bond, a well-known public
area near the Huangpu River, covering a 199.7-meter cloth scroll
with calligraphy and paintings to mark the return of Hong Kong to
the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the activity, organized by the Municipal Committee
of the Communist Youth League of China, was "Rejoice Over the
Return of Hong Kong and Create a Magnificent Future."
</P>
<P>
On one side of the scroll, the national flag and the regional
flag of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region were drawn. In
the middle is a group of Hong Kong-themed paintings, dotted with
71 exquisitely-carved seals representing 71 sites in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
On the reverse side of the scroll, the young people copied the
complete text of the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Careful planning of the scroll's design by the city's teenagers
helped to sketch the historical vicissitudes of Hong Kong and
offers a glimpse into the future.
</P>
<P>
The scroll will become part of the collection of the Shanghai
History Museum.  
</P>
</TEXT>
