<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Sets Up Teleport Linking Center to World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A teleport was launched today
in Labuan, Malaysia's first international offshore financial
center (IOFC), to Link the center to the world, the Malaysian
national news agency Bernama reported.
</P>
<P>
The Telecom Malaysia-owned Labuan Teleport, inaugurated by
Malaysian Acting Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim, is equipped with a
submarine cable station, an earth satellite station and domestic
and international telephone exchanges to provide sophisticated
telecommunication services for the IOFC.
</P>
<P>
The 4,200-kilometer-long fiber optic cable, which has cost 123
million ringgit (about 49.2 million U.S. dollars), has a
transmission capacity of five gigabit per second and is linked
with six other submarine cable stations located in other parts of
the country, mostly in East Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The Labuan earth satellite station, built at a cost of 40
million ringgit (about 16 million dollars), is capable of
providing 1,500 international telephone circuits and two
television transmissions simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said on the occasion that the Labuan Teleport is not just
a landmark for the island but its construction has boosted the
international business community's confidence in Labuan as a
leading IOFC.
</P>
<P>
"The Labuan Teleport is capable of linking Labuan with the
world and it also shows that we will not be left behind amid the
rapid changes in information technology," Anwar, who is also
finance minister, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Labuan, a federal territory off the coast of Sabah, East
Malaysia, with a size of 92 square kilometers and a population of
35,000, has been developed as an IOFC under a bill passed by the
Malaysian Parliament on October 1, 1990.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
