<HEADLINE> Philippines to Continue Wood Imports: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines will continue to be
a heavy importer of logs and lumber in the next five to 10 years
as wood consumption is growing at a rate of 2.0 percent annually,
the Forestry Management Bureau said today.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference, Forestry Management Bureau director Jose
Malvas said the country's current wood consumption is more than
2.0 million cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Based on the 2.4 percent annual population growth, the annual
growth in the consumption of wood would be ranging between 2 to
2.2 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 alone, the Philippines has to import at least 700,000
cubic meters valued at around 3.5 billion pesos (132 million U.S.
dollars) based on the prevailing world market price of about 5,000
pesos (188 dollars) per cubic meter, he said.
</P>
<P>
The planned wood imports this year are about 10 percent higher
than last year, due to the growing demand of the construction and
real estate development industries.
</P>
<P>
Malvas said the Philippines will source a big bulk of its wood
import requirements from Malaysia, with the rest to be obtained
from Papua New Guinea, South Africa, Brazil and Gabon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
