<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan-Russian Trade Shoots Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The two-way trade between Kenya
and Russia will shoot up by 50 percent this year following steady
growth over recent years, a senior Russian official said today.
</P>
<P>
Oleg Rybakov, the head of the Trade Representation of Russia
in Kenya, predicted that more than 70 Russian businessmen are to
meet their eastern African counterparts on exploring mutual trade
and investment opportunities here Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan-Russian direct trade reached at least 3.5 million
U.S. dollars last year, 3.1 million of them flowing from Russia to
the eastern African country, he told Xinhua in an exclusive
interview.
</P>
<P>
But according to Kenya's official data, the 1996 trade volume
between the two sides hit 15 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Although Kenya's share in its two-way trade with Russia is
quite small, it is getting more and more money from Russia by
exporting tea, flowers and life animals.
</P>
<P>
Kenya has been gaining strong foothold on Russian flower
market and become the leading supplier of carnations and roses to
Moscow, he said.
</P>
<P>
Russia's major exports to Kenya include steel products,
medical equipment, cars and solar panels, said Rybakov.
</P>
<P>
Russian Ambassador Boris Maiorski has also expressed
optimism about the Russian-Kenyan trade growth, saying that a
great potential still exists to be tapped to enhance the trade
relations between them.
</P>
<P>
Food stuff, including tea and coffee, account for nearly 30
percent of Russian imports, while Russia exports large quantities
of machinery and chemicals to Kenya, he noted.
</P>
<P>
However, Maiorski said some constraints, such as the absence
of necessary bank crediting and direct shipping links, as well as
the higher prices of Kenyan tea, coffee and sisal than other
countries, have hampered the mutual trade between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Russia signed two trade agreements with Kenya in 1964 and
1983 respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
