<HEADLINE> Document On Hong Kong-Taiwan Shipping Business Confirmed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Association for Relations
Across the Taiwan Straits, based in the Chinese inland area, and
the Straits Exchange Foundation in Taiwan, today sent letters to
each confirming decisions made in the Summary of the Discussion on
Hong Kong-Taiwan Shipping Business.
</P>
<P>
The inland area's organization's letter to its Taiwan counterpart
says that it agrees with stipulations contained in the document,
which was signed by representatives from the Hong Kong Shipowners
Association and the Straits Exchange Foundation of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The summary, which goes into effect on July 1, says that in the
period between entering and leaving Taiwan's ports, Hong
Kong-registered commercial ships will fly the flag of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) on the flagpole at the
ship's stern, and will fly no flag at the mast until the two sides
come to an agreement for doing so.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the document says that during the period of entering
and leaving Hong Kong's ports, Taiwan-registered business vessels
will not fly any flag at the stern or the mast until the two sides
can iron out a decision on the matter.
</P>
<P>
Commercial vessels, registered in either the Chinese inland area
or Taiwan, during the period of entering and leaving the ports of
the other side, may fly their own company flags and signal-flags.
</P>
<P>
Business ships registered in either place that want to increase
the number of or change any of their flags should get approval
from both sides, the summary says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 80,000 Drug Dealers, Addicts Imprisoned in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Iran has imprisoned nearly 80,000
drug smugglers and addicts, accounting for some 58 percent of the
inmates in the country, Persian daily Jomhuri Islami reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Assadollah Lajavardi, president of Iran's
Prisons Organization, as saying that most of those imprisoned were
small-time drug dealers and major drug dealers were hardly brought
to justice in Iran.
</P>
<P>
The official said that illiteracy is one of the main causes of
criminal activity in Iran, citing that 74,400 of the 80,000
imprisoned narcotic smugglers, or 93 percent of the total, are
illiterate.
</P>
<P>
Iran is used as a transit route to Turkey and Europe for the
drugs produced in Afghanistan and Pakistan. In the year ending
March 21, 1997, the Iranian authorities confiscated some 190
tonnes of narcotics.
</P>
<P>
Some 3,200 foreign nationals, mostly Afghans, are imprisoned
in Iran in connection with narcotic trafficking. The total
official figure of foreigners imprisoned in Iran on various
charges is 6,740. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
