<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Has 4,500 Post-doctorate Research Positions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Some 4,500 post-doctorate
research positions are currently offered in China, and in the past
two years, a total of 6,540 scholars have filled the posts to
conduct various projects, according to Zhuang Yi, director of the
Department of Experts with Ministry of Personnel.
</P>
<P>
At a two-day national meeting which opened here today, Zhuang
said that 4,000-5,000 scholars apply each year for post-doctorate
study, accounting for 40-50 percent of the total graduates per
year. Some 1,400 applicants pass the appraisal every year, and the
number is expected to grow by 15-20 percent annually in the years
to come.
</P>
<P>
China formed the post-doctorate study program in July of 1985, with
approval of the State Council, the country's highest governing
body. The central and local governments have invested a total of
300 million yuan to aid the scientific study and living costs of
the students.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that every post-doctorate student undertakes
two to three important projects during their course of study, and
40 percent of the total projects become key state-level works.
</P>
<P>
Beginning in early 1994, China's major state enterprises have
been involved in the training of post-doctorate students. A total
of nine research positions have been set up in key enterprises
such as Baoshan Iron and Steel (Group) Company and Daqing
Oilfield. Zhang revealed that more leading businesses have been
given the official go-ahead to enroll scholars this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rainstorms Hit South China Provinces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Sources from the Central
Meteorological Bureau said here today that torrential rains have
hit Guangdong and Hainan provinces in the south.
</P>
<P>
It is predicted that heavy rains will continue in the southern
part of China.
</P>
<P>
According to the bureau, from 5 a.m. on June 13 through 5
a.m. today, rain fell in areas south of the Yangtze River, most of
south China, southwest China and the eastern part of the
Qinghai-Tibet Plateau.
</P>
<P>
Rainfall in parts of Guangdong exceeded 200 mm.
</P>
<P>
According to the forecasts, heavy downpours from 60 mm. to 120
mm. will hit parts of south China and the western part of areas
south of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
Rainstorms and showers from June 17 to 19 will affect the
harvest of wheat in north China, the bureau said, warning that
hail may strike some of the fields.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the rains and heavy wind, the high temperatures
in north China are expected to drop in the days to come, the
bureau reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
