<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> a Great Creation (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The concept of "one country, two
systems" is a great creation which has reflected the strategic
boldness of vision of the Chinese leadership represented by Deng
Xiaoping and others. With Hong Kong's return to China just around
the corner, the practice of this principle in Hong Kong will soon
come into reality.
</P>
<P>
"One country, two systems", as explained by Deng Xiaoping,
means that within the People's Republic of China, the 1.2 billion
people living on the mainland will practice the socialist system,
while Hong Kong and Taiwan can retain their current capitalist
system.
</P>
<P>
The idea of "one country, two systems" was first set forth for
the solution of the Taiwan question.
</P>
<P>
In as early as the 1950s, the Chinese government considered to
solve the Taiwan question by peaceful means. In May 1955, the late
premier Zhou Enlai told a meeting of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress (NPC) that there were two possible ways
for the Chinese people to settle the Taiwan question: war or
peaceful reunification. And he pointed out that the Chinese
people, if possible, were willing to seek a peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
In April 1956, the late chairman Mao Zedong once again put
forth the ideas that "peacefulness is precious", and that "all
people loving the country belong to one family". Due to factors
like the interference of certain foreign forces, however, these
ideas failed to be put into practice at that time.
</P>
<P>
Starting from the 1970s, a number of significant changes
occurred in both the global and domestic situation. China and the
United States established diplomatic relations. The Communist
Party of China convened the Third Plenum of the 11th Central
Committee, which decided to shift the focus of work of the party
and the state to economic construction.
</P>
<P>
Under such circumstances, the NPC Standing Committee published
on January 1, 1979 a "letter to the Taiwan compatriots", in which
the principle of peaceful reunification of the motherland was
announced.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the National Day of 1981, Ye Jianying, then
chairman of the NPC Standing Committee, made a nine-point
declaration, which stated that after the national reunification,
Taiwan could become a special administrative region with a high
degree of autonomy. Taiwan can preserve its army, and its current
social and economic systems, way of life and economic and cultural
ties with foreign countries can remain unchanged. The declaration
contained the essence of the "one country, two systems" idea.
</P>
<P>
In September 1982, at a meeting with visiting British Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher in Beijing, Deng Xiaoping explicitly
put forth the concept of "one country, two systems", noting that
the concept could be applied in the resolution of the Hong Kong
question.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of this concept, the Chinese government started to
formulate its basic principles and policies for Hong Kong. The
concept was first affirmed and reflected in the revised
"Constitution of the People's Republic of China", which was
adopted at the Fifth Session of the Fifth NPC in December 1982.
</P>
<P>
The premise for the concept of "one country, two systems" is
"one country", that is, the resolution of the question of national
sovereignty and reunification. "Two systems" means that within the
People's Republic of China two different social systems,
socialist and capitalist, can coexist.
</P>
<P>
"Two systems" doesn't mean that there will be two political
entities antagonistic and repellent to each other. The socialist
system practiced in the interior areas is the mainstay, and the
two systems can promote each other for common development. This is
unprecedented in both the Chinese and the world history.
</P>
<P>
It was then written into the report on the work of the
government presented by the State Council on May 15, 1984 to the
Second Session of the Sixth NPC for examination and approval. The
session finally endorsed the concept, which helped lay down the
legal foundation for the signing of the Sino-British Joint
Declaration on the Question of Hong Kong, and for the enactment of
the Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
Hence, China's basic policy to resolve the Hong Kong question
through "one country, two systems". It is in the fundamental
interest of China to maintain Hong Kong's prosperity and
stability through the practice of "one country, two systems".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> a Great Creation (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Over the past years, Hong Kong has always played the role of a
"window" for the reform and opening up drive in the interior
areas, and of a bridge linking China to the outside world. With
the further expansion of the opening of the interior areas, this
kind of role will be continuously enhanced instead of
diminishing.
</P>
<P>
How will the concept of "one country, two systems" be put into
practice in Hong Kong?
</P>
<P>
From the political perspective, the HKSAR will carry out the
principle of "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong" with a high
degree of autonomy in accordance with the Basic Law, and the
existing capitalist system and way of life in Hong Kong will
remain unchanged for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
The HKSAR enjoys executive power, legislative power,
independent judicial power and power of final adjudication, while
the Central People's Government will only be in charge of HK's
defense and foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
From the economic perspective, the HKSAR will maintain the
capitalist economic and trade systems originally practiced in Hong
Kong, as well as its status as a free port. It can continue with
its free trade policy, and guarantee the free flow of goods,
intangible assets and capital.
</P>
<P>
As a separate customs territory, the HKSAR may, using the name
"Hong Kong, China", participate in relevant international
organizations and trade agreements, including preferential trade
arrangements. It can also maintain its current status as an
international financial center, with all existing monetary and
financial systems preserved.
</P>
<P>
All these special principles and policies the Chinese
government adopted for Hong Kong derived from the "one country,
two systems" concept.
</P>
<P>
They not only have paved the way for Hong Kong's smooth
transition and brilliant future, but also will exert significant
influence on Macao's smooth return to China and the final
settlement of the Taiwan question.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the 'one country, two systems" concept and its
practice will also provide new enlightenment for other countries
in the world in solving problems left over by history.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0072 </DOCNO>
