<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's Financial Reform Faces Strong Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government today
announced a financial reform package, which has sparked strong
opposition from the affected financial institutions, including the
Bank of Korea (BOK).
</P>
<P>
The highlight of the reform package is to unify the three
existing banking, securities and insurance supervisory bodies into
a single powerful agency, the "Financial Supervisory Board (FSB)."
</P>
<P>
In the reform, the BOK will be left mainly responsible for the
country's monetary and credit control, with its supervisory
authority over the banks going to the FBS.
</P>
<P>
The BOK had argued that it needs to retain some of its bank
supervisory authority to ensure the effectiveness in formulating
monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the reform package has also angered the trade
unions because the new supervisory board's replacement of the Bank
Supervision Board (BSB), the Security Supervisory Board (SSB) and
the Insurance Supervisory Board (ISB) is likely to result in major
job losses.
</P>
<P>
BOK's labor union announced today that it will call a strike
and demand Governor Lee Kyong-shik to step down for "selling the
central bank."
</P>
<P>
BOK union said it will join hands with the unions of the three
supervisory boards and will hold a joint press conference Tuesday
to announce their future actions.
</P>
<P>
The SSB and the ISB officials also strongly oppose the creation
of the single supervisory body, charging that the measure has
completely ignored the special nature of the relevant industries.
</P>
<P>
The SSB argues that supervision is just one of its many
functions and that the merger of supervisory powers will just
create confusion and inefficiency.
</P>
<P>
The ISS holds a similar position, saying that the insurance
sector, unlike other financial industries, has a greater role in
social welfare than in financial functions.
</P>
<P>
The ball is now in the court of the lawmakers as the government
will submit a legislation on the reform package to the National
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
But observers here predict that with the presidential election
coming up at the end of this year, both the ruling and opposition
parties are most likely to hesitate in passing such a
controversial and unpopular bill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
