<HEADLINE> Two Northern Ireland Policemen Killed by IRA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Two Northern Ireland policemen were
killed early today in the town of Lurgan, 35 kilometers south of
Belfast, and the Irish Republic Army (IRA) has claimed
responsibility for the attack.
</P>
<P>
Local media quoted police sources as saying that the two police
officers were on foot patrol when they were shot in the heads at
close range at 11:00 GMT. Security forces have sealed off the
ambush area.
</P>
<P>
IRA has been fighting for the end of British rule on Northern
Ireland over the past 28 years and more than 3,000 people died as
a result of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Northern Ireland has been tense since the IRA
resumed military attacks on security forces there after quitting a
ceasefire in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
It is widely feared that today's murder would cast a shadow on
the Northern Ireland peace process.
</P>
<P>
The multi-party peace talks on Northern Ireland peace were
resumed on June 3, but the IRA's political wing Sinn Fein was
barred from the meeting because the IRA refused to agree on a
ceasefire with the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
