<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Rules Apllied in World Youth Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Several new rules are
implemented at the Under-20 World Youth Soccer Championship in
Malaysia to open on Monday.
</P>
<P>
One of the rules, revised by the International Football
Federation (FIFA), means that goalkeepers at the tournament would
feel an unprecedented time pressure when handling the ball.
</P>
<P>
If a goalie stalls with the ball longer than five to six
seconds, an indirect free kick would be awarded to the opposing
side.
</P>
<P>
An indirect free kick will also be awarded if a goalkeeper
handles the ball directly from a throw-in by his own team.
</P>
<P>
Other rule changes include:
</P>
<P>
-- A goalkeeper is not allowed to move forwards before the
penalty kick but he could move sideways along his line.
</P>
<P>
-- Referees must strictly apply the four-step rule for
goalkeepers.
</P>
<P>
-- The ball is in play as soon as it moves from a kick-off or a
free kick.
</P>
<P>
A FIFA statement said the changes were agreed on at a meeting
in Belfast on March 1 and were designed to come into full force on
July 1. They would also take effect in any tournament beginning
before then and continuing beyond it.
</P>
<P>
The world youth tournament, which begins Monday and finishes
July 5, will be the first to apply the revised laws, FIFA said.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four national sides are divided into six groups to
compete in the tournament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
