<HEADLINE> Iran's President-Elect Calls for Enhanced Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President-elect Mohammad
Khatami today called for expansion of bilateral relations between
Iran and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
In separate cables to Pakistani President Farooq Ahmad
Leghari and Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, the 54-year-old
president-elect also urged its neighbor to promote bilateral
friendship.
</P>
<P>
In a message to President Leghari, Khatami expressed his
thanks for his message of felicitation and hoped that profound
religious and cultural ties between the two countries will grow
stronger in the future.
</P>
<P>
The president-elect also said that consolidation of the
relations between Tehran-Islamabad after the victory of the 1979
Iranian Islamic revolution has created a solid ground for
upgrading the bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
In response to Nawaz Sharif's message, Khatami expressed the
hope that the existing brotherly ties based on deep historical,
religious and cultural commonalities will be continued in the
future.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the official English daily Tehran
Times, in its editorial today on the imminent visit by Sharif to
Tehran, urged the Pakistani premier not to miss the opportunity to
remove misunderstanding between the two countries. But there is no
word on the specific date of his visit.
</P>
<P>
In spite of the commonalities calling for mutual cooperation,
the Afghan crisis has reportedly become the key of contention in
Tehran-Islamabad relations.
</P>
<P>
The daily concluded by saying that Sharif's visit to Tehran
is the best platform for both countries to remove
misunderstandings and reach a consensus on Afghanistan in order
to restore peace to the war-ravaged country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
