<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-British Airport Committee to Complete Work This Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese and British sides
agreed that the Sino-British Airport Committee is to complete its
work on June 30 after basically fulfilling its two tasks according
to the Memorandum of Understanding on the Construction of the Hong
Kong New airport and Related issues.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Zhao Jihua, senior Chinese representative
on the Sino-British Joint Liaison Group, after the two sides
finished the final meeting before Hong Kong's handover.
</P>
<P>
As from July 1, 1997, the unfinished part of the construction
at the Hong Kong new airport will be a matter within the autonomy
of the government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR), Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that all projects can be completed on schedule,
with good quality and within the previously-set budget," he said.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that experts on the Sino-British Airport
Committee visited the new airport at Chek Lap Kok and key projects
of the airport railway today and discussed matters on the
construction of the new airport after the visit.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, the Chinese and British sides under the Airport
Committee have reached agreement on many important matters
concerning the Airport Core Program (ACP) such as the overall
financial plan for the airport, the two supporting financial
agreements, the Airport Authority Bill and the building of the
second runway at the new airport, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are glad to see that the seven key projects charged with
the Hong Kong Government and the Western Harbor Crossing will be
completed and put into operation before the end of this month. We
appreciate the hard work of all departments concerned," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hugh Davies, senior British representative on the JLA, said,
"Today's visit and the meeting exactly two weeks before the
handover, suitably concludes the work of the Airport Committee.
The progress we see today is evidence of the Hong Kong
Government's efforts including the management and the cost
control."
</P>
<P>
"Pushing ahead with the Airport Core Program from July 1 will
naturally be an internal matter of the SAR Government. We are
confident that the SAR Government will continue to do its best and
will be able to help see the ACP through to the successful
completion," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
