<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
slightly weaker in range-bound trade in Sydney today.
</P>
<P>
The Local unit finished at 75.17 U.S. cents after spending the
session in a narrow 75.08 to 75.18 band, compared with the 75.3
U.S. cents at Last Friday's close.
</P>
<P>
Traders said Australian dollar trading on the day was extremely
quiet.
</P>
<P>
On the domestic front, market participants continued to mull
over the likelihood of a cut in official short-term interest rates
in the near future after recent economic data showed that economic
growth is not picking up enough to wind back the unemployment
rate, which continues to stand at around 8.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank of Australia, which last cut interest rates on
May 23, is scheduled to hold its next policy making meeting on
July 1.
</P>
<P>
Su-Lin Ong, a fixed interest economist with Hambros Australia
Ltd., said the Australian dollar remains vulnerable to the Reserve
Bank's easing bias and is likely to test the 74.5 U.S. cent level
in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 85.84 Japanese yen, down from
86.05 on Friday, and at 1.3072 Deutsche marks, up from 1.3017.
</P>
</TEXT>
