<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US to Continue Three "C" Policy in Kuwait, Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 16 -- (Xinhua) -- The United Sates will
continue to implement its three "C" policy in the Gulf with
commitment to Kuwait security and duel containment of Iraq and
Iran, U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference at Kuwait Bayan Palace here
before leaving for the United Arab Emirates to continue his Gulf
tour, Cohen said that "to summarize the United States policy to
Kuwait into three words: commitment, cooperation and
containment,"
</P>
<P>
He said that "the commitment of the United States to Kuwait's
security is strong and enduring and we demonstrated that in 1991
and we demonstrate it every day."
</P>
<P>
Cohen said that "cooperation between the U.S. and Kuwait shows
the depth of our commitment."
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.S. stored equipment in Kuwait and had
been doing regular joint exercises and training of ground, air
and sea forces jointly with Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said "we are a global power and our ability to protect
our interests and our friends around the world is bolstered by
the active security partnership such as the one we have with
Kuwait."
</P>
<P>
Kuwait and the U.S. signed a defense pact after the Gulf
War in 1991 stimulating the holding of joint maneuvers and
Kuwaiti purchase of military equipment from Washington.
</P>
<P>
But Cohen said no decision were made on the issue of
purchasing new weapons during his stay in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
He noted that "we intends to contain the threat from Iraq
and Iran" and "we will not relax the sanctions until Saddam
Hussein and Iraq comply fully with the UN resolutions."
</P>
<P>
Cohen voiced President Bill Clinton's position on Iran that
"U.S. is hopeful but skeptical" that Iran would "stop its
support to terrorism, acquiring longer range of missiles and
weapons of mass destruction."
</P>
<P>
Iran denied it has given support to terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. defense minister said "this policy of commitment,
cooperation and containment serves our country well today and
will protect our interests in the future."
</P>
<P>
On the purpose of his Gulf tour, Cohen said his tour in
this region is basically to "indicate that we intend to
remain a strong presence in the region, we commit to
Kuwait's security and preserving and protecting our interests
well."
</P>
<P>
Cohen, who arrived here Sunday, held talks with Kuwaiti
Amir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahamed Al-Sabah.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said bilateral discussions were focused on "strong
cooperation" between both countries and how to "train regularly
with the need to stress on inter operability between the
forces and to present maximum efficiency and capability for
our forces."
</P>
<P>
On talks between the Kuwaiti Amir and Cohen, Kuwaiti
Defense Minister Sheikh Salem Sabah Al-Salem, who was also
present at the press conference, said "they touched on
political issues as well as relations between Kuwait and the
United States" and principals on military cooperation between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has a military base camp in northern Kuwait
where a full brigade's military equipment exists. There are
now also around 200 U.S. jet-fighters located in Kuwait and
Saudi Arabia to monitor the southern part of Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
