<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Blasts U.S. Jerusalem Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A prominent official of the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) said today a U.S. Congress
resolution recognizing Jerusalem as Israel's undivided capital
threatens to kill the stalled Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Faisal el-Husseini, PNA Minister of Jerusalem Affairs, said
the U.S. decision on moving the U.S. Embassy in Israel from Tel
Aviv to Jerusalem is totally unacceptable to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"If this resolution is approved by the Clinton administration,
it would be the end of the peace process," Hussein warned in an
interview given today to Egypt's Voice of Arab radio.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. House of Representatives voted Tuesday calling on
President Bill Clinton to reaffirm that Jerusalem must remain
Israel's "undivided capital."
</P>
<P>
Hussein urged Clinton to reject the resolution, especially as
the crisis of the Palestinian-Israeli negotiations has reached
its peak since Israel broke ground on a new Jewish settlement in
East Jerusalem three months ago.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. government could halt this resolution similar to its
previous stance," he said, adding that such a measure would blow
up the whole peace process.
</P>
<P>
In October 1995, the U.S. Senate and the House of
Representatives passed the Jerusalem Embassy Act which states as
a matter of U.S. policy that Jerusalem should remain "the
undivided capital of Israel" and the U.S. embassy should be
moved there by May 1999.
</P>
<P>
Israel captured East Jerusalem in 1967 and has claimed the
city as its undivided capital while the Palestinians also want
Jerusalem as their future capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
