<HEADLINE> Minister on Cooperation Between Inland Areas, HK (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 16 (Xinhua) -- China's Minister of Railways Han
Zhubin said today that the railway departments of Hong Kong and
the inland areas will expand cooperation in the transportation of
passengers and container cars, as well as the operation of three
express trains.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong and the inland areas have maintained sound ties in
railway transportation for a long time, he said. With the
approaching of Hong Kong's return to the motherland, exchanges of
travelers and cargo will increase by leaps and bounds, the
minister said in an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The daily life of Hong Kong people has been closely connected
with the inland railway departments: three express trains carry
fresh and frozen foodstuffs to Hong Kong every day. The
Guangzhou-Kowloon train is one of the most convenient means of
transportation for Hong Kong residents entering the Chinese
inland areas.
</P>
<P>
There are now seven trains from the inland areas to Hong
Kong. The first Guangzhou-Kowloon train was launched on April 4,
1979. In mid-May of this year, passenger trains opened from
Beijing and Shanghai to Kowloon.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the Guangzhou-Kowloon trains alone had
carried a total ridership of more than 28 million by the end of
last year.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the Beijing-Kowloon and the Shanghai-Kowloon
railway lines shortened the distance between Hong Kong and the
large inland cities such as Beijing, Shanghai, Tianjin, Nanchang,
and Zhengzhou, Han said.
</P>
<P>
Han revealed that a number of provinces and cities recently
proposed opening tourist trains to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"In line with the need and conditions, I think it is possible
to increase some passenger trains at an appropriate time," the
minister said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Countries Receive Certificates for Consular Posts in HK SAR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 16 (Xinhua) -- China today issued certificates
for heads of the consulates of the United States, Thailand, and
the Republic of Korea in the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
The certificates were given here by Director of the Department
of Consular Affairs of the Foreign Ministry of China Zhang Hongxi
to US Ambassador to China James Ralph Sasser, Thai Ambassador to
China Nikhom Tantemsapya and Minister of the ROK Embassy to China
Bong Joo Moon.
</P>
<P>
So far, the Chinese government has reached agreements with 84
countries for reserving their consular posts in the Hong Kong
SAR. Consulate heads of 39 countries have received
the certificates from China's Foreign Ministry including Canada,
Australia and Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Through diplomatic channels, most of the 84 countries have
provided the Chinese Foreign Ministry with the names and resumes
of those candidates who are and will continue to be heads of the
consulates of their countries in the Hong Kong SAR after July 1.
</P>
<P>
The issuance of such certificates in accordance with the Vienna
Convention on Consular Relations and relevant Chinese laws is
aimed at ensuring those consulate heads in the Hong Kong SAR will
perform their duties smoothly after July 1.
</P>
<P>
The issuing work is still going on and is expected to conclude
before July 1 this year, according to the Chinese Foreign
Ministry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minister on Cooperation Between Inland Areas, HK (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Referring to the three express cargo trains bound for Hong
Kong, Han said that for years the trains played an active role in
maintaining the prosperity and stability of Hong Kong and Macao.
</P>
<P>
In the past 35 years, some 87 million pigs, 5.2 million cattle,
several billion head of poultry, 2 million tons of frozen food,
as well as a large quantity of aquatic products and vegetables had
been transported to Hong Kong and Macao, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Chinese leaders Jiang Zemin, Li Peng and Qiao Shi all
emphasized the importance of the three trains' service, and wrote
inscriptions to mark its 35th anniversary. The Ministry of
Railways also made important arrangements for the service, he
added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that after 1997, the three express trains will still
be the most advanced cargo trains in the inland areas, and their
status will be further strengthened in order to offer better
service to Hong Kong and Macao for their needs in fresh and frozen
foodstuffs.
</P>
<P>
The container transport, as another major cooperation program
between the inland areas and Hong Kong, is of great significance
to maintaining the status of Hong Kong as an international
shipping center. Han said that his ministry is willing to work
toward this end.
</P>
<P>
First, the Ministry of Railways will better operate the through
trains to transport containers between the inland areas and Hong
Kong, he said, adding that his ministry had already cooperated
with the Kowloon-Canton Railway Corporation, and started
through-train container transport service from Zhengzhou, Wuhan,
and Chengdu to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Inland cities such as Kunming, Guizhou, and Chongqing will also
open through trains to transport containers to Hong Kong, he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Han said, his ministry will take steps to expand
the cargo transport service from the inland areas to Hong Kong,
and try to gather food supplies and transport them to the region.
</P>
<P>
Han also voiced his confidence in the future cooperation
between the inland areas and Hong Kong, saying a close tie will
surely give impetus to the economic development of both sides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
