<HEADLINE> Bangladesh PM Asks for Investment from D-8 Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina today called on investors from countries of the
newly-launched Developing Eight ("D-8") group to invest in her
country.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference on her return from Istanbul after
attending the D-8 summit, Hasina said the investors could invest
in Bangladesh independently on the basis of 100 percent ownership
or through joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
She also expressed optimism that the D-8 group would play a
constructive role in the uplift of the economies of the member
countries.
</P>
<P>
The D-8 Group, initiated by Turkey and comprises Bangladesh,
Egypt, Indonesia, Iran, Malaysia, Nigeria and Pakistan, was
formally launched in Istanbul Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said the forum identified six areas of
cooperation during the summit, including trade, industry,
communications, technology, finance and health development.
</P>
<P>
"We expressed our firm determination that the combined role of
the eight Muslim countries would create opportunities for
cooperation among us," she said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to her meeting with Malaysian Premier Mahathir
Mohammad, Hasina said Malaysia had expressed the desire to set up
industries in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
"I also apprised him of the investment-friendly environment in
Bangladesh and urged the Malaysian entrepreneurs to avail
(themselves) of the opportunity," she said.
</P>
<P>
Hasina also said that she in her speech at the summit had
mentioned the success of micro-credit programs of Bangladesh in
alleviating poverty and pointed out various incentives offered by
the Bangladesh government to attract foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
The next summit of the D-8 group will be held in Dhaka in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
