<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Brewery Protests Tanzania's Likely Tariff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's biggest brewery has
issued a strong protest over a proposal to double the import duty
on Kenya beer to Tanzania, the East Africa Standard reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Kenya Breweries Ltd (KBL) placed full-page advertisements in
Tanzanian newspapers last week condemning the proposal made by
the Confederation of Tanzanian Industries (CTI) to protect local
beer.
</P>
<P>
"We sincerely hope that the (Tanzanian) Ministry of Finance
will review -- and better still, ignore -- the recommended tax
increase on PTA beers," said KBL Managing Director Michael Karanja
in a strongly worded statement.
</P>
<P>
"This will be in line with the spirit of East African
Cooperation," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The CTI proposal urged to double the current duty on beer
imported from Kenya to 14 U.S. cents a liter while leaving the
local product unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The CTI also proposed reducing the tariff on beer imported
from outside the Preferential Trade Area in Eastern and Southern
Africa. This would favor imports from South Africa and the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Kenya Breweries is a public company quoted on the Nairobi
Stock Exchange and owned Tanzania's sole brewery in Dar es Salaam
until it was nationalized in 1967.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania Breweries Ltd (TBL) now is controlled by South
African Breweries which bought the main shareholding when the
company was recently privatized.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania has been a big market for Kenyan beer over recent
years. enditem

