<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Reach Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Record gains on the New York
Stock Exchange at the weekend and investors buying into high-yield
companies sent the Australian share market to another record high
today.
</P>
<P>
"The fundamentals globally still show that share markets still
rise and that interest rates and inflation continue to go low,"
Peake Lands Kirwan senior broker Bill Richmond said.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries gained 14 points to 2669.3, eclipsing
Friday's record close high of 2655.3.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth Bank of Australia and the ANZ Banking Group
led the upward drive as market speculation continued about the
future of the banking industry.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank rose 46.1 cents, or 3.17 percent, to close at
a record high of 15 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said speculation about an easing of official monetary
policy and a special dividend and the bank's high yields pushed
its share price higher.
</P>
<P>
ANZ, which has been subject to intense speculation about a
takeover by an international bank, gained 20 cents to 9.85
Australian dollars while Westpac Bank lost 5 cents to 7.7
Australian dollars and National Australia Bank was up 5 cents to
reach 18.78 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index was 27.1 points higher at 4189.1
while the All Resources Index went up by 3.1 points to 1498.8.
</P>
<P>
Mining giant BHP rose 1 cent to 18.9 Australian dollars while
Rio Tinto gained 32.2 cents to 22.608 Australian dollars and
transport group Brambles Industries Ltd. 68 cents to 26.08
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index fell 8.4 points to 1538.7. In Sydney trading,
gold bullion closed at 340.9 U.S. dollars an ounce, compared with
341.25 dollars on Friday.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 351.79 million shares worth 850.81
million Australian dollars (638.1 million U.S. dollars), with
rises outnumbering falls 628 to 569.  
</P>
</TEXT>
