<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Calls on ICO to Condemn Turkish Incursion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's Foreign Minister Mohammed
Saeed al-Sahhaf has called on the Islamic Conference Organization
(ICO) to live up to its responsibility and condemn Turkish
incursion into northern Iraq, the Iraqi News Agency (INA)
reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a letter addressed to ICO Secretary General Hamid al-Gabid
Sunday, the foreign minister said that ignoring this aggression
would encourage Turkey, a member of ICO, to go on violating the
principles of the organization in respecting sovereignty, unity
and independence of other member states.
</P>
<P>
On May 14, about 10,000 Turkish troops, supported by tanks
and air force, crossed into northern Iraq to attack Turkish
anti-government Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) rebels, who have
bases in the region. Ankara said its troops will not withdraw
until they achieve their military goals.
</P>
<P>
It is incumbent on the organization to ask Turkey to pull out
its forces from Iraqi territory and to avoid any hostile
attempts in the future that might have negative effect on the
historical relations between the Arab nation and Turkey and on
their common interests, al-Sahhaf added.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Iraq reserves the right to appropriate
retaliation for such military acts and to compensations for the
damage they caused to civilians and property.
</P>
<P>
The minister called on the Turkish government to reconsider
its policy vis-a-vis the situation in northern Iraq, asking
Ankara not to interfere in Iraq's internal affairs and pay
special attention to the cooperation between the two neibors.
</P>
<P>
Media reports said that up to 100 tanks have crossed back into
Turkey since Friday in the Turkish army's partial withdrawal from
northern Iraq, but an Iraqi official in the Ministry of
Information and Culture told Xinhua that up till now, there is no
official confirmation about Turkish withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry Spokesman Omer Akbel Sunday denied
the reports that Turkey has begun to withdraw its troops from
northern Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
