<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Protest Against U.S. Congress Bill on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Several dozens of Palestinians
held a demonstration before the U.S. consulate in East Jerusalem
this morning in protest against the U.S. congressional resolution
recognizing united Jerusalem as Israel's capital.
</P>
<P>
Last Tuesday, the U.S. House of Representatives voted 406-17
to recognize Jerusalem as the undivided capital of Israel,
despite the opposition from the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
The house also voted to provide 100 million U.S. dollars for
moving the U.S. Embassy to Israel from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem in
1999.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians, who see East Jerusalem as the capital of a
future Palestinian state, sharply criticized the resolution,
which they say will hurt the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
During today's demonstration, Faisal Husseini, senior
Palestinian National Authority official on Jerusalem affairs,
submitted a letter of protest to U.S. Consul in Jerusalem Edward
Abington.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Husseini warned that if the U.S. approves
the resolution, "the whole peace process will be lost."
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Council Member Ziad Abu Ziad, who also
participated in today's demonstration, said the resolution is a
"very grave" affair since Jerusalem is one of the central disputed
issues in the final status talks between Israel and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Most countries in the world, including the U.S., have not
recognized Israel's annexation of East Jerusalem following the
Middle East war in 1967.
</P>
<P>
It has been the position of successive U.S. governments that the
city must never be divided again, but its future must be settled
through negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
