<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Artists Create Masterpiece for Hong Kong's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nanchang, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Artisans are putting the final
touches on a big ceramic painting to be given to Hong Kong to
greet its return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The 1.97 m. by 0.97 m. work is called "The Return of Bauhinia
to the Peony's Embrace". The bauhinia symbolizes the Hong Kong
Special Administration Region and the peony is supposed to
represent China.
</P>
<P>
The work is a collaborative effort by ten top artists in
Jingdezhen in southern Jiangxi Province, which is known as China's
porcelain capital. Nine of them drew the design on paper, and the
tenth, a 64-year-old well-known Chinese painting and porcelain
master, Zhang Songmao, painted it.
</P>
<P>
Zhang calls this painting a condensation of 50 years'
experience. He has worked more than 12 hours a day for the past 40
days, just to make sure every detail is complete.
</P>
<P>
The work is now ready for the kiln, to fix the color. "When
completed, it will be a masterpiece which represents the artistic
level and craftsmanship of the 'capital of porcelain arts'," says
an expert based here, who adds, "More importantly, it is a token
of our joy over the return of Hong Kong." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
