<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Pursues Guided Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is pursuing a policy of
guided privatization, Foreign Minister Chief Anthony Ani said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the eighth Gamji lecture in Kaduna, the minister
said the government will not deliberately sell off all its
investment in some companies and public establishments.
</P>
<P>
The government wants to ensure that when some equities are
sold to foreign investors, that part of the foreign capital
coming into the country has some elements of technology, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chief Ani added that the government is considering
establishing a public trust to which proceeds from privatization
would be pooled.
</P>
<P>
The trust would be managed by former heads of state and would
be used in developing the nation's health, education and
agriculture sectors, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister disclosed that a total of 4.3 billion Naira
(about 50 million U.S. dollars) would be distributed to about
8,154 communities nationwide to support the development of
cottage industries under the Family Economic Advancement Program
(FEAP).
</P>
<P>
The FEAP was introduced by the government in this year's
budget as a major measure to boost rural economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
