<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hotel Tax Threatens Olympic Sponsorships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A disputed state tax on hotel
rooms in the New South Wales is threatening sponsorships for the
2000 OLympic Games in Sydney, Australian Olympic Committee
president John Coates said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Coates said in Sydney that state Premier Bob Carr has
threatened to confiscate hotel rooms for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
He said the dispute -- in which 17,000 hotel rooms are being
withheld from Olympic use by Sydney hotel owners -- could endanger
up to 400,000 U.S. dollars worth Olympic sponsorships.
</P>
<P>
The 10-percent hotel tax is set to begin on September 1 and is
estimated to be worth about 38 million U.S. dollars a year to the
state government.
</P>
<P>
Coates, who recommended a phasing-in of the tax, said some
sponsors might renege the deals because the Australian Olympic
Committee could not fulfill its promise of accommodation
packages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
