<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Role for EU Investment Bank in Stability Pact Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Investment Bank
(EIB), one of the world's largest development agencies, is
expected to play an important role in fighting unemployment in the
European Union (EU) countries.
</P>
<P>
The EIB could support several job-creation projects, said a
diplomat at the EU Amsterdam summit meeting which started this
morning.
</P>
<P>
Swedish Finance Minister Erik Asbrink, who attended the talks
among EU finance ministers on Sunday night, has confirmed that the
use of EIB credits would help the 18 million unemployed in the
15-nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
France has been demanding that more attention be paid to
employment issues in the run-up to the launch of the European
Economic and Monetary Union in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
It wants funding for major infrastructure programs such as
Trans-European Networks (TENs) as a way for creating jobs. TENs
include large road, rail and telecommunications links between and
within the 15 EU member countries.
</P>
<P>
But Germany has ruled out the costly Europe-wide job-creation
programs, which, it argues, have in the past merely raised
inflation and interest rates and failed to cut unemployment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
