<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Inflation Rate at 21.4 Percent in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's inflation rate dropped
slightly to 21.4 percent in April from 22.4 percent in March this
year, according to the Federal Office of Statistics (FOS).
</P>
<P>
The figure is in contrast with that of 18.5 percent released by
Finance Minister Anthony Ani last week, which suggests a decline of
3.9 percent in the month under review.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper This Day today quoted a top FOS official as
explaining that what the finance minister released was the projected
figure for April sent by FOS to the Finance Ministry some two months
ago.
</P>
<P>
The FOS, a government agency that collates, processes and
distributes statistical data for the country, has told the ministry
with a caveat that it should not in any way be taken as the final
figure.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government's efforts to bring down consumer
prices have paid off in recent years. The inflation rate dove
substantially from 72.8 percent in 1995 to 28 percent in 1996. In
the first three months of this year, it dropped to 26 percent,
24.4 percent and 22.4 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Despite signs of improvements in the country's macroeconomic
situation, observers noted that trend of inflation rate decline may
suffer a setback as consumer prices started to rise in March this
year.
</P>
<P>
A FOS document last week disclosed a price rise of 3.9 percent
in March from the previous month due to the upward movement of
prices of food items throughout the country. And the repeated fuel
scarcity that has slowed down economic activities nationwide add
weigh to the government to curb the already increasing prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
