<HEADLINE> China Developing Anthracite Coking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, June 16 (Xinhua) -- China's vast anthracite reserves
can now be prepared for industrial use, thanks to new technology
developed by several institutes in north China's Shanxi province,
China's largest coal producer.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that it allows 80 percent of the raw coal to be
used for coking, largely meeting the world demand for coking coal,
and giving additional value to anthracite.
</P>
<P>
In the past, anthracite could not be coked with ordinary coking
methods and every year large amount of anthracite powder were
wasted and caused heavy pollution.
</P>
<P>
But the anthracite can be directly coked in its area of origin,
decreasing the transport volume and making better use of raw
materials for coking in China, one local researcher said.
</P>
<P>
According to a local source, this technology has been applied
by a number of counties in Shanxi, which plans to build an
anthracite coking business with a yearly output of one million
tons by the beginning of the next century.
</P>
<P>
The technology was jointly developed by the institute of
anthracite coking of Shanxi Normal University, the Changcheng Coal
Mine in Puxian county, and the East China Metallurgy College.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
