<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian PM Confident Of D-8 Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal
el-Ganzouri said today the newly launched D-8 group will foster
closer economic links among the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian news agency MENA quoted Ganzouri as making the remark
after briefing President Hosni Mubarak on the establishment of the
group at a summit in Istanbul, Turkey, Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The eight most populous Muslim countries, namely Egypt, Turkey,
Pakistan, Iran, Nigeria, Bangladesh, Malaysia and Indonesia,
signed a declaration launching the Developing-8 (D-8) economic
group.
</P>
<P>
Following his meeting with Mubarak, Ganzouri said the main aim
of the D-8 group is to promote economic ties among member states,
which need coordination to boost their production and exports to
the world.
</P>
<P>
He said the trade exchange among the member states, which is
400 billion U.S. dollars annually, does not exceed one percent of
their total trade volume with the other parts of world.
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri said Egypt's membership in the new group does not
contradict its presence in Arab groupings or within the
Organization of African Unity or affect the Egyptian-U.S. and
Egyptian-EU partnership.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Turkey, Ganzouri delivered a message from
Mubarak to Turkish President Suleyman Demirel on the Turkish
incursion into northern Iraq and Israeli-Turkish military
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak sent a message to Demirel last week in which he
expressed the Arab world's concern at the month-long Turkish
operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
