<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Games Head Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The executive chairman of the
1998 Commonwealth Games organising committee resigned on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Retired-General Hashim Mohamed Ali, who had been criticised by
two cabinet ministers over preparations for the event, told a news
conference that he had sent a letter of resignation on Monday to
acting Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
"I personally sent the resignation letter to the office of
acting Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim this morning,"
Hashim said.
</P>
<P>
Youth and Sports Minister Muhyiddin Yassin and and Culture,
Arts and Tourism Minister Sabbaruddin Chik had criticized the
organizing committee for failing to publicize what will be the
biggest sporting event ever held in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Kuala Lumpur is expected to stage the biggest ever Commonwealth
Games in September 11-21 next year with 15 sports attended by
6,000 athletes and team officials from 69 countries. 
</P>
