<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PLA Troops Groomed to Serve Needs of Hong Kong (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Shenzhen, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Chen Jianjun, an infantryman of a
unit of the Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA) to be stationed
in Hong Kong, never expected that a speech of his would win him
such high regard from some Hong Kong compatriots.
</P>
<P>
On May 12, 1996, a group of celebrities from Hong Kong visited
the Eighth Company of the PLA Hong Kong troops where Chen
serves. At the company's club, they invited Chen to sing a
song in Guangdong dialect.
</P>
<P>
After his hearty rendition, Chen said: "It's Mothers' Day
today, so please let me express my heartfelt blessings to those
mothers among our distinguished guests, as well as to our
motherland."
</P>
<P>
As soon as Chen concluded his performance with these eloquent,
touching words, he won loud applause from the guests. One visitor
said:"I never expected to hear such a moving speech from a tough
soldier."
</P>
<P>
Since their debut exposure to the public in January 1996, the
PLA Hong Kong troops' top military qualities and good cultural
levels have created for themselves the image of being a mighty
and civilized force. For this they have won the admiration and
respect of Hong Kong compatriots from all walks of life.
</P>
<P>
On a hot summer's day last year, more than 600 people came over
from Hong Kong and watched a military display staged by the PLA
Hong Kong troops.A performance by scout troops was particularly
fascinating and impressive.
</P>
<P>
As soon as the order was given, a group of 26 scouts, gathered
in front of a four-storied 13-meter-high building, began to climb
up the facade of the building -- with their bare hands. They had
neither ladders nor ropes, but used wall corners, windows,
balconies and drain pipes of the building as their support. They
seemed to defy gravity, and in a matter of a few tens of seconds
were looking down from the roof of the building.
</P>
<P>
The PLA Hong Kong troops also displayed their shooting and
fixed-bayonet skills.
</P>
<P>
Li Ka Shing, member of the Preparatory Committee for the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region said after watching the
performance that a powerful national defense is a reliable
guarantee for the unification, economic development and social
prosperity of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
He added that there was no need to be skeptical about
prosperity and stability in Hong Kong as such a strong force would
be taking up the defense duty in Hong Kong after its return to the
motherland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PLA Troops Groomed to Serve Needs of Hong Kong (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It is not only the first-rate military qualities of the PLA Hong
Kong troops that impressed many Hong Kong compatriots, but also their
cultural qualities.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Andy Wong Kam Din, a teacher at Hong Kong Polytechnic was
one who was once quite doubtful about the cultural qualities of
the PLA troops destined for Hong Kong duty. His day in Shenzhen
made him change his mind.
</P>
<P>
"In the barracks I saw that bedside cupboards of many soldiers
contained various books ranging from world literary classics,
books on science and technology to those on language and law. The
troops are knowledgeable and quite familiar with Hong Kong's
history.They are au fait with current world affairs and some of
them even speak English," he said.
</P>
<P>
"These soldiers are very young, polite and affectionate," said
Ng Tai-yin, a 78-year-old Hong Kong man when asked about his
impression of the PLA Hong Kong troops.
</P>
<P>
Ng was one of more than 1,000 Hong Kong compatriots who
visited the barracks in May 1996 to meet the PLA Hong Kong
troops. During the visit, Ng said everyone was impressed by the
clean and tidy appearance of the barracks as well as its
well-disciplined officers and men. But what impressed Ng most was
their courtesy and good manners.
</P>
<P>
"They saw I was old and tired, so pulled up a chair for me, sat
me down and poured me a cup of tea," Ng recalled.
</P>
<P>
"On July 1, 1997 when the PLA formally enters Hong Kong, I'll
go out and welcome them, even if I will have to walk with a
stick," he said.
</P>
<P>
During the spring of this year, Wong Keising, a 67-year-old
Hong Konger, travelled to Shenzhen. When he toured Shenzhen
reservoir, a major fresh water resource for Hong Kong, he happened
to meet a group of soldiers: the PLA Hong Kong troops. They were
voluntarily planting trees on a hillside to ensure a clean water
source for Hong Kong people. When Wong realized this he was very
moved.
</P>
<P>
"Even before their arrival in Hong Kong, I felt their deep
affection for Hong Kong people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Whether the PLA Hong Kong troops will abide by the laws in Hong
Kong after they arrive is a question concerning many Hong Kong
compatriots. Many Hong Kong journalists have explored this
question, and time and time again their conclusion was " yes."
</P>
<P>
In a room back in the PLA Hong Kong troops' barracks hang many
calligraphic inscriptions written by Hong Kong compatriots. Some
praise the PLA Hong Kong troops as "The Great Wall of the
Motherland and the guards of Hong Kong", others describe them
as a civilized law-abiding model force, while more express their
expectations for the stationing of the PLA troops there, saying
that the force will secure stability and prosperity in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The collection reflects the wishes and expectations of all
Hong Kong people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
