<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Villagers Relocated to Make Way for River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 16 (Xinhua) -- "We've really left our old home,"
murmured Wang Chuanyi, standing on the bank of the Yellow River
watching the immense flowing waters, a month after he had settled
into his new place.
</P>
<P>
The 72-year-old farmer had spent most of his life alongside the
second largest river in China, which is known as the cradle of
Chinese civilization, but which is also known for its seasonal
fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
Last October, the provincial government of Shandong in east
China started a program to relocate villages that lay in the path
of waters that would rise as the result of dams being built on the
river. The move kills two birds with one stone, according to local
officials. One thing the dams do is to make the flow of the river
steadier and safer and the other the move does is help remove the
villagers from extreme poverty.
</P>
<P>
"Last year, all farmland was destroyed by floods and we had to
live on government subsidies," said Li Xinfang, a villager. The
frequent floods stymied all efforts to develop local farming and
industries, he noted. And last year's were the worst in nearly 20
years. They inundated more than one million ha. of farmland and
affected over 10 million local people.
</P>
<P>
Under the resettlement plan, some 420,000 people from over 760
villages in Shandong will be involved. More than 280,000 of them,
from over 580 villages, will be resettled, according to Zhao
Kezhi, a provincial official in charge of the project.
</P>
<P>
He says that the scheme will cost more than 1.6 billion yuan,
and apart from 310 million yuan from the provincial government,
the bulk will come from local governments and the people who are
intended to benefit from it.
</P>
<P>
"Lack of funding is still the main obstacle to this program,"
Zhao explained, "but the provincial government is determined to
put it into effect and it is seen as the only solution to the
issue."
</P>
<P>
So far, a number of well-designed villages have been built for
the resettled villagers, and nearly 10,000 people, or eight
percent of the total, have been relocated, Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
"Now flooding is nothing to us now," said Li Xiu'e, a woman who
has moved to the new Lijinshitang Village which now houses people
from 12 villages.
</P>
<P>
"I have a two-story house," said Li Yancai, from the same
village. "My family lives on the second floor and they've opened a
shop on the first floor," he noted.
</P>
<P>
School-children are among the happiest group of people, because
they no longer have to sit in drab classrooms with worn-out desks
and chairs. Six new schools have been set up in Liangshan County
for children of the resettlement program. The schools have
three-story buildings, good teachers, and standard facilities and
equipment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 10:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Libraries Superior to Internet, Research Finds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Libraries are still a more
accurate source of information than the Internet, thus students
should not confine their research only to the Net, according to a
Bar-Ilan University researcher in Israel.
</P>
<P>
David Schwartz, a researcher of the university's school of
business administration, compared materials on various subjects
found in the world's three major libraries, the U.S. Library of
Congress, the New York Public Library, and the British Royal
Library, to Internet researches he carried out on the same topics.
</P>
<P>
In each case, Schwartz said, the representation of the topics
on the Internet was inferior to that in the three libraries.
</P>
<P>
Many Internet sites are profit-oriented, so one can not always
trust the information provided by vested interests, he added.
</P>
<P>
"The Internet has opened up a treasure of information for
researchers and seekers of knowledge throughout the world, and it
has become common practice to turn to the Internet as a convenient
source of information," he said.
</P>
<P>
He questioned the effectiveness of Internet int is presenting
knowledge.
</P>
<P>
It is a foregone conclusion that the Internet will become the
infrastructure for a global digital library, he continued, "but
this is still years away from happening." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
