<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan President Vows to Crush Opposition Rallies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
has vowed to crush the opposition rallies scheduled to be held in
nine towns on Saturday with no permit from the government.
</P>
<P>
The rallies may cause dire consequences, the Daily Nation
newspaper today quoted Moi as saying.
</P>
<P>
The organizers are only interested in inciting violence and
causing bloodshed, he said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Heavy security has been deployed in Kisumu, the third largest
city in Kenya, and some other planned rally venues, he added.
</P>
<P>
All the leaders and supporters of the ruling party Kanu should
use all means to ensure no unlawful meetings to be held, he
urged.
</P>
<P>
FORD-Asili Chairman Kenneth Matiba and his National Development
Party counterpart Raila Odinga announced the rally plan on June 6
in a bid to put more pressures on the government to conduct
constitutional reforms before the forthcoming general elections.
</P>
<P>
Under the current constitution, if a candidate wins no
less than 25 percent of votes respectively in five of the eight
provinces of Kenya, he can be qualified as a legal president.
</P>
<P>
Now the opposition leaders urged to change the clause,
demanding the future president get more than 50 percent of the
total votes nationwide otherwise form a coalition government with
other parties. This has already been refused by Moi.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government banned and then broke up the first two
rallies of opposition parties last month amid turmoils which
injured dozens of people and caused businesses in downtown
Nairobi to come to a complete standstill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
