<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Migrant Detention Center Closes in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The entire Whitehead Detention
Center for Vietnamese migrants (VMs) closed down today after
eight-and-a-half years' operation as a result of the continued
fall in the VM population.
</P>
<P>
The main camp was closed on January 3 this year when the number
of VMs and Vietnamese illegal immigrants (VIIs) dropped to 6,300.
</P>
<P>
"With the continued fall in the VM and VII population to about
1,900, there is no need to maintain a camp at Whitehead," Refugee
Coordinator Sally Wong said. "The remaining 260 there have been
transferred to the High Island Camp."
</P>
<P>
High Island Detention Center is the only major VM detention
center left in Hong Kong. It now holds over 1,400 VMs and VIIs
after the closure of Whitehead.
</P>
<P>
"Since 1989, we have successfully repatriated about 67,000 VMs
and over 1,000 VIIs to Vietnam," Wong said. "Another 143,000
Vietnamese refugees (VRs) have been resettled elsewhere."
</P>
<P>
With the successes in repatriation and the declining VM
population, VM detention centers have been closed down
progressively. The Tai A Chau Detention Center was closed in
September 1996, the main camp of Whitehead Detention Center in
January 1997 and the Kai Tak Vietnamese Migrant Transit Center in
March this year.
</P>
<P>
"We are pleased that the transfer operation today at Whitehead
has proceeded smoothly," Wong said. "The closing of the whole
Whitehead Detention Center is a landmark achievement in the final
chapter of the whole VM saga."
</P>
<P>
The Whitehead Detention Center, located at Sha Tin, was first
opened in January in 1989 when the VM population in Hong Kong
stood at about 11,000. When the VM population reached its height
of nearly 60,000 in October 1991, the center provided
accommodation for about 25,000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0143 </DOCNO>
