<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Long Scroll of Painting to Mark Hong Kong's Return Completed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A 1,997-meter-long scroll of
paintings done by 1,000 young people from Shenzhen and 997 young
people from Hong Kong was completed Sunday in a stadium in
Shenzhen, a city bordering on Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The long scroll of paintings is said to be the world's longest
by the Guiness Book of Records Office in Shanghai, which awarded
it a certificate.
</P>
<P>
Each piece is 100 centimeters long, representing 100 years of
great changes in Hong kong, and 97 centimeters in width,
symbolizing the returning of Hong Kong to the motherland in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The paintings has 10 parts on 100 years of great changes, the
beautiful motherland, unity among people of all nationalities, the
oriental pearl, one country and two systems, centennial ceremonies,
and the bright future.
</P>
<P>
The work was sponsored by the Shenzhen Youth Federation,
Shenzhen Work Committee of the Chinese Young Pioneers, and a
Hong Kong youth committee for activities to mark Hong Kong's
return to the motherland. It will be housed at the Shenzhen
Museum.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
