<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundupp:  Verbal Battle over Endangered Animal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The 10th conference of the
Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES)
in Harare is turning out to be a verbal battle.
</P>
<P>
Participants are arguing heatedly over 75 proposals involving
85 species since it started on June 9.
</P>
<P>
The western countries and wildlife conservation extremists are
opposed to listing of trade bans on any endangered species from CITES
appendix one to appendix two and are campaigning strongly to have
resolutions in favour of the stance they take regarding wildlife
preservation.
</P>
<P>
Some governments of the CITES member nations have submitted
proposals emphasising sustainable use of renewable natural resources.
</P>
<P>
The African elephant became a focal point in the argument at the
conference.
</P>
<P>
Three southern African neighbours, Botswana, Namibia and Zimbabwe,
have proposed that the African elephant be downlisted from the CITES
appendix one to appendix two, which would allow for limited and
controlled trade in the elephant and its products.
</P>
<P>
All southern African countries are supporting the proposal. They
said the seven-year trade ban on ivory had stopped culling operations
to maintain sustainable increasing levels of elephant populations.
The three states have a combined elephant population of about 150,000
which is growing with disastrous consequences for the rural people.
</P>
<P>
They also held elephants in much of southern Africa are not an
endangered species and are in fact a danger to the environment and
human life because of their large and increasing number which is now
out of control and threatening the survival of other wild species and
the whole ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
But the western countries and animal rights groups such as the World
Wildlife Fund do not agree and insist the proposal to downlist the
elephant be rejected by the CITES.
</P>
<P>
They said donwlisting the elephant would open floodgates for the
widespread slaughter of both African and Asian elephants to service
an insatiable international illegal trade in ivory.
</P>
<P>
The animal lovers are even prepared to source funding for elephant
conservation programs if African range states destroy their ivory
stockpiles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Verbal Battle Over Endangered Animal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Minke whale is another hot issue at
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Japan, one of the world's leading fishing nations, is proposing
that international trade in four species of whales be allowed because
of what it says is an abundance of stocks, particularly the minke
whale.
</P>
<P>
The Icelandic government argued that minke whales were in
great number in both the northern and southern hemispheres. The
South-Pacific Economic Power also argued that the number of minke
whales worldwide was conservatively estimated at over one
million, and the abundant species of these whales should never
have been put on the endangered species list.
</P>
<P>
With thick documents and glossy pictures to buttress its point,
the International Fund for the Welfare of Animals (IFWA) said the
Japanese proposal should be rejected outright, adding it contains
many false and unsupported claims about the minke whale population.
</P>
<P>
CITES adoption of Japan's proposal at this stage, claims the IFWA,
would bring CITES into conflict with the International Whaling
Commission, which is the global authority for regulation of whaling.
</P>
<P>
The IFWA further argued that meat of other protected whale species
is frequently sold in Japan in the guise of minke whale meat.
</P>
<P>
South Africa voiced support for a strictly controlled legal trade
in rhino horn and other products, saying that the proposal would
reduce illegal activities.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, which has a white rhino population of between
7,200 and 7,500, is proposing that restrictions preventing
international trade in rhino and other products be lifted.
</P>
<P>
South Africa held the trade ban had not been effective in
providing protection for rhinos. Only those populations that have
been effectively protected and managed have maintained their numbers
or increased.
</P>
<P>
However, the Environmental Investigation Agency has called for
the outright rejection of the proposal by South Africa, saying it
would have negative consequences, including directly threatening
all other species of rhino both in Africa and Asia.
</P>
<P>
Tomorrow, the 138 CITES member countries will vote to make final
decisions on the 75 proposals. The people in the world are waiting
for the results. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 07:36 </DATE_TIME>
