<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israelis Wounded by Roadside Bomb in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Two Israeli soldiers have been
wounded in an attack in south Lebanon claimed by the pro-Iranian
Hezbollah, or Party of God, Beirut's newspaper Daily Star reported
Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
The Israelis were injured when a remote-controlled roadside
bomb exploded Sunday night as their armored car, accompanied by a
foot patrol, was rolling on the road between Bint Jbeil and Saf
Al-Hawa on the edge of the central sector of the so-called
"security zone".
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued in Beirut, the Islamic Resistance, the
military wing of Hezbollah, claimed responsibility for the
attack.
</P>
<P>
The attack was confirmed by Israeli Radio today, saying four
soldiers were injured in the bomb attack and one of them died in
hospital later.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Sunday, Hezbollah guerrillas attacked two Israeli
positions at Qantara and Mashaaroun in the Israeli self-carved
buffer zone with around 40 mortar shells, causing no casualties.
</P>
<P>
The assaults came a day after an Israeli soldier was seriously
injured during a assault on the Ghazlan post.
</P>
<P>
Police sources said Israeli artillery responded to the attacks
by pounding suspected Hezbollah positions in the valleys opposite
the zone, but no casualties were reported.
</P>
<P>
The latest clashes brought to 10 killed and some 45 wounded the
Israeli casualties in south Lebanon so far this year.
</P>
<P>
Israeli warplanes carried out reconnaissance flights over the
south Lebanese areas of Nabatiyeh and Iglim Al-Toffah Monday
morning.
</P>
<P>
Two Israeli jet fighters appeared in the clear blue sky over
the capital of Beirut at 8:55 a.m. (05:55 GMT).
</P>
<P>
Syrian and Lebanese anti-aircraft army units on the hills
around the city refrained from firing at the invaders.
</P>
<P>
Hit-and-run attacks by guerrillas and retaliatory bombardments
by the Israeli forces and their client Lebanese militia
constitute a daily scene in south Lebanon, the last active
battlefront of the Arab-Israeli conflict.
</P>
<P>
Israel established the 1,100-square-kilometer "security zone"
in 1985 ostensibly to protect northern Israel from cross-border
attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
