<HEADLINE> New Book for Return of Hong Kong Published </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A book of 600 photos from the
history of Hong Kong, many of them appearing for the first time,
has been compiled and released by Xinhua News Agency and United
Publishing (Holding) Ltd. of Hong Kong here today as a special
album to greet the return of Hong Kong to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese-English book, titled "Hong Kong", has three
parts: "Historical Changes", "Economic Upsurge", and "Road to
Return".
</P>
<P>
An overseas edition will be published in Hong Kong on June
18. The publishers say that it shows a history that must be
remembered by the Chinese nation, and conveys the Chinese people's
wishes for the region's future.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee-Hwa, the first Chief Executive of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region, did the calligraphy for the book's
name.
</P>
<P>
Qian Qichen, vice-premier and minister of Foreign Affairs,
wrote its preface, where he says, "The compilation and publication
of the book is to remember the humiliation the Chinese nation
suffered one hundred years ago, and to wish Hong Kong a brighter
future. It is a significant event."
</P>
<P>
Guo Chaoren, president of Xinhua, headed the book's compilation
committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Hong Kong's Future Guaranteed - Malaysian Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's diplomatic envoy in
Hong Kong today expressed his firm belief in China's Hong Kong
policy and the work of the future HK Special Administration Region
Government in guaranteeing HK's long-term stability and
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
"The return of Hong Kong to China is a most significant
historic event since it (together with the return of Macao to
China) marks the end of colonialism in Asia," said Zakaria,
Commissioner for Malaysia in Hong Kong in an exclusive interview
with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"The significance also lays in the fact that the handover will
enable Hong Kong people to become masters of their own society and
to determine their own destiny and future by themselves for the
first time," noted the career diplomat, who has 22 years of
experience behind him.
</P>
<P>
In his office overlooking Victoria Harbor in the showcase
"Malaysia Building" in downtown Hong Kong, Zakaria told Xinhua
that he does not share some apprehensions expressed about the
future of Hong Kong. On the contrary, he is part of the majority
who are fully convinced that Hong Kong will have a bright future
after the handover.
</P>
<P>
Zakaria, who came to Hong Kong nine months ago after serving a
three-year diplomatic tenure in London, said he began to follow
closely the Hong Kong issue in London and has been fully convinced
that the Basic Law and the policy of "one country, two systems"
will be strictly observed.
</P>
<P>
"This will enable Hong Kong to enjoy a high degree of autonomy
and to continue the free economic and trade practices and to
retain its entrepreneur spirit", he said.
</P>
<P>
All the economic indicators, especially that of the stock and
property market, illustrate that Hong Kong's economy is still at
its height after so many years of fast growth, adding support to
people's upbeat mood, he observed.
</P>
<P>
He is also convinced that HKSAR Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
and his colleagues have been doing their best to look at various
problems facing them so as to ensure continuity in policies and an
efficient government after the handover.
</P>
<P>
"All these will enable the long-term stability and prosperity
of Hong Kong. And since Hong Kong is a major international trade,
financial, shipping and tourism center, such stability and
prosperity will contribute not only to the Asian-Pacific region
but the world's development as a whole," said Zakaria, who served
as a diplomat in Japan, Thailand, Indonesia and Britain.
</P>
<P>
In his view, those who hold pessimistic views and wrote
negative reports about the future of Hong Kong are not familiar
with or even ignorant about the region.
</P>
<P>
With a long history of economic and trade ties, Hong Kong has
become an important source of capital and know-how in the
development of Malaysia's manufacturing sector. In 1996, Malaysia
was Hong Kong's eleventh largest trading partner, with trade
volume increasing by 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
Zakaria believed that since Hong Kong is an important gateway
to China, its return to China will surely help enhance the
bilateral economic and trade ties with Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
He said Hong Kong's return to China has aroused great attention
among Malaysians. The Malaysians living in Hong Kong are among the
first of foreign communities to agree to take part in a floats
parade organized by the Hong Kong Committee for Celebration of
Reunification with China on July 2.
</P>
<P>
"The response is so enthusiastic we have to turn down
applications for limited space", he said.
</P>
<P>
The 44-year-old Malaysian diplomat who is an avid reader of
books of Chinese history and literature, said that he is most
happy to be chosen to work in Hong Kong when it is turning a new
leaf in history.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hot Wave Hits China's Icebox </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A sudden heat wave hit Harbin,
known as "ice city" in Heilongjiang Province, Saturday and Sunday,
turning it into one of the hottest cities in China.
</P>
<P>
Temperatures in this northernmost capital city of China during
the two-day period reached 36 degrees c., following a period of
lower than normal temperatures.
</P>
<P>
The local people, who are used to fresh breezes in the summer,
began to look for ways to deal with the unexpected turn of the
weather. Trucks were busy spraying water on local highways and
other public places, and cold drinks shops were crowded. Zoo
workers installed water pipes to provide a "water curtain" animals
could walk through to avoid heat-stroke. Veterinarians added
Chinese herbal medicines to feed for the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
Sales of air conditioners were double the normal rate, and
hundreds of thousands of local people crowded the banks of the
Songhuajiang River each day to enjoy the cool air.
</P>
<P>
According to the provincial meteorological department, the hot
wave was caused by a hot-air mass coming from Inner
Mongolia. Temperatures are expected to fall in a few days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environmental Protection In North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, June 16 (Xinhua) -- North China's port city of Tianjin
has seen some progress in environmental protection in recent
years, without sacrificing rapid economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that over 98 percent of the city's drinking
water is now up to state standards, its "green" coverage is up to
22 percent, and three state-level natural reserves have been set
up.
</P>
<P>
The old industrial base has increased its pollution controls at
construction sites, and some 94 percent of the large and
medium-sized projects have had a pollution assessment done by
local environmental control departments.
</P>
<P>
The city closed 89 small factories with serious pollution
problems last year, while encouraging cleaner production in other
factories.
</P>
<P>
Liu Jinsheng, the director of the City Bureau of Environmental
Protection, says that the city government regards pollution
controls as a way to improve living conditions for the city's
residents, and because of the growing environmental awareness, it
has been receiving several hundred complaints and suggestions from
the public each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Insists on Ivory Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Despite international pressure to
protect endangered animals, Zimbabwe insists on its trade of
elephant products, the local daily the Herald reported today.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe will sell ivory without approval from the Convention
on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES), rather
than accept a ''compromise'' that would see the African elephant
downlisted to the CITES appendix II.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's Minister of Environment and Tourism Chen
Chimutengwende said in an interview at the weekend that a refusal
to accept the Zimbabwean proposal would not be a solution to the
country's elephant management problem.
</P>
<P>
On the secret ballot, the minister said this should be accepted
without a problem. But he dismissed the possibility of exchanging
''debt for ivory'' as a ''diversionary negotiating tactic'' by those
opposed to the southern African countries' proposal.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Botswana and Namibia have proposed that the African
elephant be downlisted from the CITES appendix I to appendix II
which would allow for limited and controlled trade in the
elephant and its products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
