</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Economic Success to Stay in Post-handover HK, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The experiment of "one country,
two systems" will work and all the factors contributing to Hong
Kong's economic success will stay intact after the handover,
Douglas Henck, chairman of the American Chamber of Commerce in
Hong Kong (AmCham), told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of the transitional year, Henck took the
chairmanship of the chamber, which, grouping some 1,100 American
companies, is the largest American chamber of commerce outside the
United States.
</P>
<P>
He highlighted the results of the 1996 AmCham business
confidence survey -- the seventh of its kind -- which indicated
that the American business community are bullish over the
post-handover business climate in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
An all-time high of 95 percent of AmCham member companies see
the business environment as either "very favorable" or "favorable"
for the next five years up to 2001, compared with 91 percent in
1995 and 81 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Henck noted, there is also a shift from
"favorable" to "very favorable", reflecting "a very significant
improvement in the confidence".
</P>
<P>
Henck moved here in 1987 to set up a regional office for Aetna
-- a leading American insurance group founded in the middle of the
19th century. Now he is the senior Aetna executive in the region
and is responsible for overseeing the Asia-Pacific operations of
the group.
</P>
<P>
In his eyes, Hong Kong stands out as a world-class business hub
because of, among other factors, the rule of law, low taxes,
government's non-interference policy, fine infrastructure, and
free flow of information.
</P>
<P>
"In terms of road, airport, telephone and the equipment you
have here, the quality of workers and the education of people, the
central location in Asia," no other cities in Asia can be Hong
Kong's peers, except maybe Singapore, Henck said.
</P>
<P>
Asked about whether he believes that these factors,
constituting a very favorable business environment, will be
preserved after July 1, Henck replied: "Yes, I do."
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law really provides the underpinning, the foundation,
for all of these things to stay the same, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"When I gave speeches in the United States about Hong Kong, one
of the things I do is spend 20 minutes talking about all of the
factors that would stay the same," Henck said.
</P>
<P>
"It is only by understanding that foundation, then you can
discuss the concerns that people have heard about; it is only by
understanding how many good things are continuing the same, then
you could have an intelligent discussion on anything else," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on some Western media reports intent on predicting a
gloomy picture for Hong Kong, Henck said, "Newspaper reporters are
always looking for stories that sell newspapers. It's true a
headline which is a little frightening can sell more newspapers
than a headline which is good."
</P>
<P>
There are some people in Hong Kong who are "purposefully trying
to scare the rest of the world, that does not help," Henck
stated.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed that the Special Administrative Region will
be acting autonomously and that the business climate will continue
to be good.  
</P>
</TEXT>
