<HEADLINE> Philippine Rebel Commander Killed in Attack on Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A Philippine Muslim rebel commander
was killed early this morning when a group of rebels he led
attacked an Army detachment near Cotabato city in western
Mindanao, the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The attack occurred just on the eve of the fifth round of
initial peace talks scheduled on June 17-18 between the separatist
Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) and the government in a
university in Cotabato, capital of Maguindanao province.
</P>
<P>
Capt. Noel Detoyato, spokesman of the Army's Sixth Infantry
Division, said the raiders were led by a certain Commander
"Shotgun" Gazali, who was killed during a brief exchange of
gunfire.
</P>
<P>
The rebels retreated after learning their leader had been
killed, Detoyato said, adding that no casualty was reported on the
government side.
</P>
<P>
Also today, Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF vice-chairman for political
affairs, said the group is carefully studying the latest proposal
of the government peace panel to implement a general ceasefire
agreement in areas where the MILF operates.
</P>
<P>
The proposal seeks to abolish the old interim local truce in
Buldon town in Maguindanao, which the government panel said is
very limited and would be replaced by a broader one.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is expected to announce its position on the matter
during Tuesday's talks.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a breakaway faction of the former larger rebel
group of the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF), which had
already signed a peace deal with Manila last September.
</P>
<P>
The government has sought to forge a similar peace accord with
the MILF, which is currently the largest anti-government force in
the country and is considered more radical than the MNLF.
</P>
<P>
The government and the MILF began their exploratory peace talks
early this year, but the talks have been on-and-off because of
sporadic fighting between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The MNLF and the Muslim extremist Abu Sayyaf group are the only
two Muslim groups still fighting the government forces. The Abu
Sayyaf has shunned peace talks with the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
