<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Finance Ministers to Resume Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Belgian Finance Minister
Philippe Maystadt said Sunday that European Union (EU) finance
ministers would meet again on Monday morning to discuss the
stability pact.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting of the finance ministers on Sunday night,
Maystadt told reporters he hoped that an agreement could be
reached.
</P>
<P>
Dutch Finance Minister Gerrit Zalm, whose country holds the
rotating EU presidency, told a press conference that progress had
been made in finalizing a stability pact designed to curb
government spending in the forthcoming Economic and Monetary Union
(EMU) and guarantee a stable European single currency Euro, which
will be introduced on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
"We made extremely good progress. We will be able to finish a
text on stability pact Monday," he said.
</P>
<P>
The stability pact, agreed on in principle at a Dublin EU
summit last December after tough negotiations, is due to be
formally approved by EU heads of state and government at their
summit meeting Monday in Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
The EU ministers are trying to round off a draft European
Council Resolution on growth and employment to supplement the pact.
</P>
<P>
France has been demanding more attention to employment issues
in the run-up to the launch of the EMU and wants funding for
major infrastructure programs such as Trans-European Networks
(TENs) as a way to create jobs. TENs include large road, rail and
telecommunications links between and within member countries.
</P>
<P>
However, Germany has ruled out costly Europe-wide job-creation
programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
