<HEADLINE> Tudjman Set to Be Reelected as Croatian President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Croatian President Franjo Tudjman
looked certain to be reelected to a five-year term in Sunday's
presidential elections, according to preliminary results.
</P>
<P>
Tudjman won 59.09 percent of the votes, while his opponents
Social Democrat candidate Zdravko Tomac and a nine-party coalition
candidate Vlado Gotovac garnered 22.82 percent and 18.09 percent
respectively, the country's election commission announced
mid-night on Sunday after counting more than half of the votes.
</P>
<P>
First elected as president in 1990, Tudjman won the reelection
bid in the country's first direct voting for presidency in
1992. His third winning is widely expected due to his contribution
to achieving independence of Croatia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
