<HEADLINE> Qatar Begins Preparations for Economic Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Qatar has begun preparations to
host a Middle East and north Africa (MENA) economic summit due to
take place in November despite Arab opposition to sitting together
with Israel, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Six committees have been set up to prepare the summit, the
fourth annual event since 1994, Gulf News reported from the Qatari
capital Doha.
</P>
<P>
Qatar expects that around 2,500 participants will attend the
summit. Almost 1,500 hotel rooms have been reserved for the
participants, including 800 officials, 800 businessmen, 300
representatives of regional and international organizations, and
100 economic experts, the newspaper quoted an official from one of
the committees as saying.
</P>
<P>
Qatar's Emir Sheikh Hamad bin Khalifa al Thani confirmed
Friday that his country will also invite Israel to attend the
summit.
</P>
<P>
In Tel Aviv, Israel, Israel's Federation of Chambers of
Commerce confirmed that it has received assurance from Qatar for
being invited to the conference, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Syria has drummed up opposition to the conference because of
deadlock in the Middle East peace talks. Arab League foreign
ministers called in March for a freeze in any normalization of
relations with Israel after it began construction of a new Jewish
settlement in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Qatar and Oman established economic ties with
Israel. But plans for expanding such ties have been put on hold
because of strained Arab-Israeli relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
