<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Introduce New Airports Policy Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A comprehensive airport policy
is being finalized by India's Civil Aviation Ministry to lay down
guidelines for all future private sector investments in airport
projects in efforts to develop the crucial infrastructure, a
government official said today.
</P>
<P>
Whether foreign companies can hold a majority equity stake in
airport projects is under discussion among government departments
concerned.
</P>
<P>
The quantum of foreign equity for airport development was
likely to exceed the present 40 percent ceiling stipulated for
domestic air operations, as the government was in favor of
allowing foreign companies to invest majority funds in
capital-intensive infrastructure projects, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign companies are allowed to form joint ventures with
Indian firms and foreign equity up to 40 percent has been
permitted in operating domestic airlines. But there has been no
proposal yet to grant permission to bring 100 percent foreign
equity for airport development.
</P>
<P>
The airport development policy will also include a framework
for related projects such as multi-storeyed parking lots, hotels
and other airport infrastructure facilities, the official added.
</P>
</TEXT>
