<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fire Engulfs A Gas Field in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Fire expert teams from Singapore and
United States are flying into Bangladesh to fight an ever-biggest
gas field fire which is still ranging today, said an official at
Bangladesh Oil, Gas and Mineral Corporation.
</P>
<P>
A massive explosion in a gas well in Moulvibazar under
northeastern Sylhet division early Sunday sent fires leaping up to
160 meters.
</P>
<P>
There has been no report of casualties. However, many people
were missing, said a worker who escaped unhurt, and the
authorities have asked people in nearby villages to remain on red
alert.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said that an area of about one and a half square km
was engulfed by the fire in the Magurachhara natural gas field,
which is being operated by Occidental of Bangladesh Ltd, a United
States company.
</P>
<P>
There were two explosions of such type in Sylhet in the 1950s
and in Chittagong in the 1960s respectively, but the fires caused
by these blasts were not as big as the present one.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina, who was in a visit to Turkey on
Sunday, has asked all officials concerned to take immediate
measures to fight the fire.
</P>
<P>
All fire brigades in Sylhet division were kept stand-by. But
fire brigade officials said it was beyond their capacity to
control the raging blaze.
</P>
<P>
The fire, which has destroyed property worth tens of thousands
of U.S. dollars, including rig, trailor cars, cranes, also damaged
nearby rail tracks, cutting off direct rail transport from Sylhet
to the capital city Dhaka and Chittagong.
</P>
<P>
A high-level inquiry commission, comprising representatives
from local administrations and Occidental, has been formed to
investigate the cause of the devastating fire.
</P>
<P>
Some engineers said the fire broke out as gas was found at a
very early stage of drilling while they thought it would take very
deep digging.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government signed production-sharing contracts
two years ago with Occidental and another firm on exploration of
gas in eight out of 23 blocks in the natural gas-rich country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
