<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 16 (Xinhua) -- India will need a massive 150
billion rupees (about 4.23 billion US dollars) investment over the
next decade in the crucial infrastructure sector to sustain annual
economic growth of 7-8 percent, said the government's latest study
published today.
</P>
<P>
India's per capita electricity consumption was less than
one-tenth of the global average and the penetration ratio of
telephone was still low at 1.5 per 100 people as compared to the
global average of 10 per 100, the study said.
</P>
<P>
Infrastructure development held the key to the country's future
development, it said.
</P>
<P>
Though infrastructure was a major bottleneck, its development
also presents enormous opportunities for investors, particularly
foreign direct investors, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Aware of this potential, the Indian government has taken some
initiatives to attract foreign investment, particularly in the
power sector, allowing 100 percent foreign participation.
</P>
<P>
Besides, a five-year tax holiday is provided and it is followed
by a deduction of 25 percent for the next five years for
build-operate-own-transfer (BOOT) projects in power, roads,
high-ways, bridges, airports, ports, rail systems, water supply,
irrigation, sanitation and sewerage systems.
</P>
<P>
Similar deductions are being considered for the
telecommunications sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
