<HEADLINE> Tianjin Foresees Hi-tech Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A large international computer
fair will be held in North China's Tianjin from August 13 through
16. It's the latest stride the city is taking into its future,
according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The China International Computer and Networking Show will bring
dozens of international computer vendors and their most advanced
computer hardware, application software, mass storage peripherals,
networking and communications and office management systems.
</P>
<P>
More than 70,000 visitors are expected at the show sponsored by
the Tianjin municipal government, the Ministry of Electronics
Industry and International Data Group of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Mayor Qu Weizhi said the fair will provide Tianjin with
the opportunity to become acquainted with the latest computer
technologies and promote international co-operation.
</P>
<P>
Qu said the show will also help the city's Information Port
Project, considered a key step toward Tianjin's goal of becoming
an international metropolis.
</P>
<P>
The project, started last year, will be completed in 2010. It
involves setting up 11 applications systems, nine databanks, a
public communications network and an information exchange network.
</P>
<P>
The applications systems cover banking and finance, commerce,
foreign trade, taxation, insurance, scientific research and
education.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government has promised financial support to the
project and to provide preferential policies to attract foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
With the completion of the project, Tianjin will become a main
manufacturing center for information technology equipment, with a
solid public communications network backbone and advanced
technological support.
</P>
<P>
Information technology is one of the municipal government's key
industries to be developed during its Ninth Five-Year Plan
(1996-2000). Tianjin was selected by the State to test
computer-aided-design technologies and business management
automation programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
