<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Fresh violence erupted in
Bangkalan, a town on the island of Madura in Indonesia's East Java
province Saturday night when hundreds of people torched scores of
buildings and cinemas, Radio Indonesia and SCTV, a private TV
station reported this morning.
</P>
<P>
The violence broke out at a ceremony held by the local
authorities to celebrate winning the Adipura Award (city
cleanliness) at around 8:00 p.m.
</P>
<P>
The rioters stormed the arena -- plunging the revelry into
disarray.
</P>
<P>
They rampaged through the town until midnight when police and
troops were able to control them, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The rioters burned and damaged a cinema, banks, shops,
government offices, cars and houses of worship, the reports quoted
local police as saying.
</P>
<P>
At least seven government officials were injured in the unrest
and 26 people were arrested, SCTV said.
</P>
<P>
The situation returned to normal Sunday after dozens of police
and troops were deployed to the location, added the reports.
</P>
