<HEADLINE> Thailand's Major Imports Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's imports of five major
products decreased sharply in the first eight months of the 1997
fiscal year starting on October 1 last year.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics by the Thai Customs Department,
chemicals imported by the country during the period dropped by
20.4 percent, followed by completely built vehicles by 17.8
percent, and paper by 11.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Imports of machinery also fell by 6.5 percent, while those
electrical appliances imported went down by 2.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The department attributed the decrease to the continued
economic downturn in the country, indicating that the country's
customs revenues have been affected due to the decreased imports.
</P>
<P>
The department said that it only raised 72.33 billion baht
(2.89 U.S. billion dollars) in revenues during the eight months,
12 percent below the target.
</P>
<P>
The department sets a customs revenue target of 125.99 billion
baht (5.04 billion dollars) for the whole fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
