<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CSCEC Eyes World Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Asia-Pacific region,
witnessing a new era of fast economic growth, remains the target
for Chinese building contractors engaged in the worldwide
construction market.
</P>
<P>
"We are optimistic about a more dynamic international market,
with the Asian-Pacific area as the center," today's China Daily
quoted Xu Peng, vice-president of the China State Construction
Engineering Corporation (CSCEC), as saying.
</P>
<P>
Formerly the State Construction Engineering Administration,
CSCEC is now China's flagship transnational construction group
under direct supervision of the State Council. It was restructured
into a corporation in 1982.
</P>
<P>
More than 90 percent of CSCEC's overseas construction business
has been in the Asia-Pacific region, including Hong Kong, Macao,
Viet Nam, Pakistan and other regions and countries.
</P>
<P>
Since 1979, Chinese building firms have begun to compete in the
world contracting market and their business has been growing.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, it ranked 34th in the world's 225 largest contractors
and the world's seventh biggest housing constructor, according to
Xu.
</P>
<P>
CSCEC's annual overseas turnover grew to a high of 1.59 billion
US dollars last year, almost four times the 430 million US dollars
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
CSCEC has built more than 3,100 projects abroad, ranging from
schools, hospitals, factories, dams, power stations, airports,
irrigation systems, land reclamation, highways and bridges to
housing and municipal facilities. It also has undertaken many
foreign-aid construction projects.
</P>
<P>
According to Xu, one of CSCEC's showpiece projects under
construction in Asia is the 10 billion HK dollars terminal
building of the new airport in Hong Kong. CSCEC is undertaking the
project with four overseas companies. The airport, which costs
more than 50 billion HK dollars, to open in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Xu noted CACEC also hopes to extend its business to other parts
of the world, such as Europe, the Middle East and the United
States, although he confessed "market competition in the regions
has been crucial."
</P>
<P>
Besides overseas branches, the 150,000-member State-owned
corporation includes eight domestic construction engineering
sub-bureaus, six domestic building design institutes and 44
domestic sub-companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
