<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investments Surge in Philippine Economic Zones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Investments in the Philippines'
economic zones surged to 92 billion pesos (3.5 billion U.S.
dollars) in the first five months this year, compared to the 14
billion pesos (530 million dollars) a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The latest investment level has already exceeded by 23 percent
the government-set target of 75 billion pesos (2.9 billion
dollars) for the entire year, today's press reports quoted
Economic Zone Authority Director-General Lilia de Lima as saying.
</P>
<P>
Investments for economic zones' development projects accounted
for the bulk of 52 billion pesos (about 2 billion dollars) with
the approval of 14 new economic zone projects.
</P>
<P>
According to De Lima, the authority was confident that the
10-billion-dollar exports target for the country's economic zones
this year would be surpassed.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines has so far established 53 economic zones all
over the country, which have become one of the country's major
foreign reserve earners in recent years.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, exports from these economic zones reached 6.5 billion
dollars, accounting for more than one-third of the country's total
exports that year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
