<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Civil Servants' Commitment Vital to HK's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The total commitment of civil
servants to serving the people of Hong Kong is vital to Hong
Kong's future, said Chau Tak Hay, Secretary for Broadcasting,
Culture and Sport.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua, Chau said, "I firmly
believe Hong Kong has a brilliant future, but that would require
the joint efforts from Hong Kong people as well as Hong Kong's
180,000 civil servants."
</P>
<P>
Having served for almost 30 years at Hong Kong's civil service,
the 54-year-old secretary has worked successively as
Director-General of Trade, Secretary for Health and Welfare,
Secretary for Trade and Industry, and Secretary for Broadcasting,
Culture and Sport.
</P>
<P>
Chau studied economics at the University of Hong Kong, where he
obtained a Bachelor of Arts degree in 1967. He believed that,
while what he had studied in university was not directly relevant
to his work, university education did provide him with the basic
analytical and problem-solving skills required to meet the many
challenges in his career.
</P>
<P>
Starting when he was in his twenties, Chau had participated for
many years in international negotiations on the export of Hong
Kong's textiles and clothing. He recalled that Hong Kong,
together with other developing countries and regions, had to face
unfair and discriminatory treatment by the developed countries in
those negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The constant need to defend Hong Kong's interests vigorously
had instilled in him a strong attachment and a deep commitment to
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
From 1979 to 1984, he was stationed in Geneva as Hong Kong's
permanent representative to the General Agreement on Tariffs and
Trade (GATT). He was Hong Kong's Secretary for Trade and Industry
from 1991 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
The frequent contacts and exchanges with the outside world help
him take a world view in looking into all matters.
</P>
<P>
Sine 1995, he has served as Secretary for Broadcasting, Culture
and Sport. He will also serve in the same position after July 1,
1997 in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong's position as a broadcasting hub in the Asia-Pacific
region is constantly being challenged by other cities in the
region," he said. The HKSAR must ensure that its broadcasting
policies, particularly those on satellite TV broadcasting, are
attractive to regional broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
"Freedom of the press is one of the major factors contributing
to Hong Kong's success as an international financial and business
center," Chau said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that press freedom was one of the freedoms guaranteed
by the Basic Law. He was confident that freedom of the press
would be maintained after July 1.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Tung Chee Hwa, Chief Executive of the HKSAR,
had time and again assured Hong Kong people that they would
continue to have freedom of the press and expression.
</P>
<P>
On cultural policy, Chau said that it was natural that after a
hundred and fifty years' separation from the motherland, many Hong
Kong people did not have a very deep understanding of Chinese
history and culture.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the promotion of patriotism as well as national
history and values was entirely compatible with the maintenance of
an open and democratic society.
</P>
<P>
He felt that the process should start within the education
system first. Recent archaeological discoveries in Hong Kong
could also serve to cultivate a greater attachment among Hong Kong
people to Chinese history and culture.
</P>
<P>
In his spare time, Chau likes to watch news programs as well as
Chinese historical drama series on TV. During his recent trips to
Beijing, he bought video cassettes of TV dramas including "Empress
Wu Zetian", "Romance of Three Kingdoms", "Emperor Ming Huang of
the Tang Dyansty" and "Stories about the States of the Eastern
Zhou Dynasty".
</P>
<P>
He also enjoys watching movies, opera and reading. He said, "I
am an optimist by nature and I am very optimistic about Hong
Kong's future" he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
