<HEADLINE> Colombian Rebels Release 70 Government Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The Colombian
Revolutionary Armed Forces (FARC), the largest rebel group in the
country, today freed 70 government soldiers who had been held for
months.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers were handed over to the representatives from the
International Committee of the Red Cross and the Colombian
Committee for National Reconciliation at the town of Cartagena Del
Chaira in southern Colombia.
</P>
<P>
An international monitoring group, including former Costa Rican
President Rodrigo Carazo and President of the Peace Commission of
Guatemala Manuel Conde Orellana, attended the hand-over ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Sixty of the released soldiers had been captured on August 30,
1996 when the FARC attacked a government military outpost in
southern Colombia. Thirty-one soldiers were killed and 20 others
injured during that skirmish.
</P>
<P>
The other 10 were captured in an ambush in Choco province in
January this year.
</P>
<P>
In return for the release, Colombian President Ernesto Samper
accepted a FARC condition to demilitarize a 13,200-square
kilometer jungle zone in the Caguan River valley as of May 23.
</P>
<P>
The representatives from the Colombian government and the FARC
signed an agreement on June 3, fixing the date for the release of
the 70 soldiers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Not Ready to Liberalize Finance Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will not submit an
improved offer to liberalize its finance sector by the target date
of July 14 required by developed members of the World Trade
Organization (WTO), a senior Thai official said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's commitments should be fulfilled based on a
progressive process as the government has to take into account the
development level of local businesses and their readiness to meet
competition, said Krirk-Krai Jirapaet, Thai ambassador to the WTO.
</P>
<P>
Thailand also will take time to assess other members' offers,
he said in a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Some developed members, like the United States, Canada, the
European Union and Japan, insisted that the target date be met so
negotiations at WTO level could be settled by December this year,
according to Krirk-Krai.
</P>
<P>
Industrial powers are pressing other members, especially
Southeast Asian countries, to scrap all restrictions on foreign
investment in banking and insurance services, in particular in
foreign shareholdings and issuance of licenses for foreign banks
and insurance companies, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Some other developing members are also not to submit their
offers to meet the July 14 target date, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
