<HEADLINE> Xiamen Expects 400,000 Overseas Tourists in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Xiamen City in east China's Fujian
Province expects to host 400,000 overseas tourists this year,
60,000 more than in 1996, according to the local Tourism Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Overseas tourists may spend about 250 million US dollars in
this city, the bureaus says, adding that the number of domestic
visitors will remain at about five million, with the tourism
industry's revenue reaching 4.8 billion yuan in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Xiamen is a special economic zone and home to many overseas
Chinese. Those from Japan, the Republic of Korea, Hong Kong,
Macao, Taiwan, and other southeast Asian countries and regions
have a deep interest in the folklore, gardens, temples, coastal
waters and mountains in this area.
</P>
<P>
As one of the ten major tourist attractions in the country,
Xiamen is paying attention to the construction of infrastructure
facilities, such as the pay telephone system using magnetic cards,
hotels, road signs and lighting. The city has taken the lead in
adopting the international standard of ISO9000 to improve the
quality of service.
</P>
<P>
A dozen tourist programs have been scheduled for 1997,
including the Xiamen Tourism Festival toward the end of June and
the International Piano Festival for the Youth and a food
exhibition in October.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, trial direct shipping services between Xiamen and
Taiwan will bring more tourists from that island to this city, the
local Tourism Bureau says.
</P>
<P>
It also says that Xiamen is speeding up the legislation of a
set of regulations on tourism management to further ensure the
rights and interests of travel agencies and tourists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
