<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Tax Authorities Clamp Down on Evaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Tax authorities in south China's
city of Shenzhen, a boom town neighboring Hong Kong, are clamping
down on tax evaders and declaring that adamant offenders would be
severely punished.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen Honochi Golf Leisure Club, a Sino-Japanese joint
venture, was recently found guilty of evading taxes totalling 70
million yuan. After the several warnings went unheeded by the
company, the local tax authorities in April confiscated 13 million
yuan from its bank accounts and publicly auctioned 10 of its
vehicles as its punishment.
</P>
<P>
Local sources said the company still refused to pay up the
remainder of the amount due.
</P>
<P>
"Including the fine, the amount of money related to the case
has hit 130 million yuan, becoming the largest tax evasion case in
China," according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
The punishment imposed on the company has exerted a strong
impact on similar offenders.
</P>
<P>
According to the tax authorities, a Japanese-funded steel
company, stunned by the action, recently approached the local tax
bureau and delivered 1.6 million yuan in back taxes due between
1994 and 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
