<HEADLINE> EU Finance Minister Still in Discussion on Stability Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Finance Ministers of the
European Union are still in discussion late Sunday night on the
pact on stability and growth, on which differences emerged among
EU's 15 member states.
</P>
<P>
The informal working dinner of the ministers was planned from
19:00 GMT to 21:00GMT. According to the latest information the
meeting could last a few more hours.
</P>
<P>
The ministers have to round off a draft European Council
Resolution on growth and employment, to supplement stability pact,
a measure designed to curb excessive spending by governments
inside monetary union and guarantee a stable euro, due to be
introduced on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
France has been demanding more attention be paid to employment
issues in th run-up to the launch of the EMU and wants funding for
major infrastructure programs such as Trans-European
Networks(TENs) as a way for creating jobs. TENs include large
road, rail and telecommunications links between and within member
countries.
</P>
<P>
But Germany has ruled out costly Europe-wide job-creation
programs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
