<HEADLINE> Annan Calls for Peaceful Solution to Congo Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 15 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan today urged the parties in Congo Brazzaville to seek
peaceful solution to their conflict.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General continues to be concerned about the
precarious situation in Congo Brazzaville," said a statement by the
U.N. spokesman's office.
</P>
<P>
"He is gratified that the parties have agreed to seek a
negotiated solution to the conflict, and he urges them to
respect the cease-fire," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, Annan also expressed his gratitude to the
Government of France for the excellent way in which it carried out
the evacuation of all foreign nationals, including the staff of
the United Nations, other international organizations and
non-organizations.
</P>
<P>
The conflict started in June after the government army
surrounded rebel leader Denis Sassou Nguesso's home as part of a
crackdown on private militias and unauthorized armies in the run-up
to a July 27 election.
</P>
<P>
The two sides declared a truce on Wednesday. But the fighting
resumed on Sunday after two days' lull. It is reported that the
envoys of the two sides left the capital earlier today for peace
talks in Gabon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
