<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Jobs Summit in October Possible: Luxembourg Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Luxembourg may call a special
summit meeting in October to address the European Union's high
unemployment, a spokesman for the Luxembourg delegation said on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"Several countries have approached us and we would be willing,"
Guy Schuller, spokesman for Luxembourg Prime Minister Jean-Claude
Juncker, told Reuter Newsagency.
</P>
<P>
The possibility of a jobs summit was immediately confirmed by
Junker himself, whose country will hold the next six-month EU
presidency from July.
</P>
<P>
"Some countries have come with the idea of this. It seems to be
excellent under the condition that we know clearly what we want,"
Juncker told French daily Le Figaro in an interview to be
published in Monday's edition.
</P>
<P>
France demands that the issue of unemployment, which currently
affects one in nine EU citizens, should be dealt with as the
priority at the EU Amsterdam summit on Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A job summit was being seen by EU officials on the sidelines of
the meeting as one possible way to acknowledge the demands of the
new French socialist government without making immediate promises
to commit funds to job creation schemes.
</P>
<P>
France has been demanding more attention be paid to employment
issues in the run-up to the launch of the Economic and Monetary
Union on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
It wants funding for major infrastructure programs such as
Trans-European Networks(TENs) as a way for creating jobs. TENs
include road, rail and telecommunications links between and within
the 15 EU member countries.
</P>
<P>
But Germany has ruled out costly Europe-wide job-creation
programs, which, it argues, have in the past merely raised
inflation and interest rates and failed to cut unemployment. Bonn
believes that the way to fight joblessness is through structural
reforms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
