<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Small Firms Lose Heavily to Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The cost of crime to the small
business sector is almost 6 billion pounds (9.6 billion US
dollars) a year, according to a report from the British Chamber of
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
The survey revealed that the average cost of a burglary is
5,865 pounds (9,384 US dollars), while the average cost of
vandalism is 2,595 pounds (4,152 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The BBC has called on Home Secretary Tack Straw to help small
businesses in response to "this staggering bill".
</P>
<P>
The survey of 505 small companies showed that they expect to
suffer from crimes as a matter of course.
</P>
<P>
It said that "85 percent of small businessmen are resigned to
the fact that they expect their businesses to be victimized at
some point in time".
</P>
<P>
Half of the respondents to the survey said that their business
had suffered from crimes in the past year, with each business being
hit three times on average.
</P>
<P>
Ian Peters, BBC deputy director-general, said: "The cost of
crimes on the small business community is totally unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
"It affects all of us as it inflates prices, reduces
competitiveness and costs jobs," Peters added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
