<DOCNO> XIE19970616.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Troops Begin Withdrawing from Congo Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The 1,250 French troops stationed in
Brazzaville today began to withdraw from the Congo Republic after
completing their week long "Pelican Operation" of evacuating
foreigners, despite a "strident" appeal by Congolese President
Pascal Lissouba to them to stay.
</P>
<P>
French troops flew away the last group of 88 foreigners from
Brazzaville this afternoon to send them to Pointe-Noire in western
Congo which was spared of the fighting, and the Gabonese capital
Libreville, said French officials.
</P>
<P>
French troops evacuated a total of 6,000 foreigners, including
1,600 French nationals, since they began their operation on June
9, said the French military.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, fighting resumed between the government troops and
the "Cobras" militiamen of former President Denis
Sassou-N'Guesso today in Brazzaville, on the eve of peace talks by
the warring sides to be held in Libreville.
</P>
<P>
"Cobras" launched offensive against government forces in a
bid to capture an air base of government troops near the
Brazzaville airport and the parliament building, according to
Agence France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
One of the representative of Sassou N'Guesso, Ambroise
Noumalazaye, said that the militiamen were responding to
bombardments by government forces on "three very populous
districts of Brazzaville" Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
"The reprisals had as purpose to destroy the origin of the
firings and crush the dorsal spine of the forces of President
Lissouba," he said.
</P>
<P>
Congolese officials estimate that from 2,000 to 3,000 civilians
were killed in the violences which broke out on June 5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
